1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:01,954
[SPEAKER_47]: Do you want to come with me?

2
00:00:01,974 --> 00:00:03,777
[SPEAKER_47]: You'll see all sorts of things.

3
00:00:04,278 --> 00:00:05,840
[SPEAKER_25]: Monsters from the past.

4
00:00:06,321 --> 00:00:07,864
[SPEAKER_25]: Aliens from the future.

5
00:00:07,884 --> 00:00:10,768
[SPEAKER_47]: The day the earth died in a ball of flames.

6
00:00:11,029 --> 00:00:11,910
[SPEAKER_47]: It won't be quiet.

7
00:00:12,251 --> 00:00:13,152
[SPEAKER_47]: It will not be safe.

8
00:00:13,172 --> 00:00:14,514
[SPEAKER_47]: And it won't be calm.

9
00:00:14,775 --> 00:00:15,416
[SPEAKER_47]: Will be.

10
00:00:15,616 --> 00:00:19,322
[SPEAKER_47]: Dead Ringers Election Special next Thursday at 10 on BBC2.

11
00:00:31,722 --> 00:00:40,999
[SPEAKER_22]: Just where do the parties plan to spend your money?

12
00:00:41,319 --> 00:00:42,161
[SPEAKER_22]: All the issues.

13
00:00:42,582 --> 00:00:43,343
[SPEAKER_22]: All the angles.

14
00:00:43,744 --> 00:00:45,046
[SPEAKER_22]: The General Election.

15
00:00:45,367 --> 00:00:46,609
[SPEAKER_22]: All on the BBC.

16
00:00:57,710 --> 00:01:00,020
[SPEAKER_47]: This is BBC One.

17
00:01:00,402 --> 00:01:05,003
[SPEAKER_47]: Now live from London, a Question Time Leaders Special with David Dimbleby.

18
00:01:36,995 --> 00:01:37,376
[SPEAKER_30]: Good.

19
00:01:37,396 --> 00:01:38,037
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you very much.

20
00:01:38,618 --> 00:01:39,720
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, good evening.

21
00:01:39,780 --> 00:01:42,445
[SPEAKER_30]: Welcome to a very special edition of Question Time.

22
00:01:42,785 --> 00:01:50,779
[SPEAKER_30]: With just a week to go until polling day, tonight the leaders of the three main British political parties are going to face questions from our audience here.

23
00:01:51,160 --> 00:01:53,945
[SPEAKER_30]: Carefully chosen to be a cross-section of voters.

24
00:01:54,346 --> 00:01:55,628
[SPEAKER_30]: And, as always,

25
00:01:55,608 --> 00:02:00,452
[SPEAKER_30]: The people in the chair won't have prior knowledge of the questions that are going to be put, nor of the points that are going to be made.

26
00:02:00,953 --> 00:02:05,957
[SPEAKER_30]: And as always, you can comment on what you hear at home, if you want to, by texting us 83981.

27
00:02:06,518 --> 00:02:09,981
[SPEAKER_30]: And if you go to CFAX page 155, you'll be able to see what other people are saying.

28
00:02:10,381 --> 00:02:14,745
[SPEAKER_30]: Or you can, as always, email us bbc.co.uk slash question time.

29
00:02:15,206 --> 00:02:18,028
[SPEAKER_30]: Now, Charles Kennedy for the Liberal Democrats will go first.

30
00:02:18,509 --> 00:02:20,671
[SPEAKER_30]: Then Michael Howard for the Conservative Party.

31
00:02:21,031 --> 00:02:24,454
[SPEAKER_30]: And finally, Tony Blair, Prime Minister for the Labour Party.

32
00:02:24,794 --> 00:02:25,615
[SPEAKER_30]: So,

33
00:02:25,595 --> 00:02:27,378
[SPEAKER_30]: Will our first challenger sign in, please?

34
00:02:42,422 --> 00:02:42,783
[SPEAKER_30]: All right.

35
00:02:44,245 --> 00:02:47,350
[SPEAKER_30]: Our first question, Mr Kennedy, comes from James Gray, please.

36
00:02:48,123 --> 00:02:53,669
[SPEAKER_37]: How am I supposed to understand your economic policies if you don't, and if you do, can't explain them coherently?

37
00:02:54,410 --> 00:02:56,953
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, certainly.

38
00:02:57,053 --> 00:03:07,124
[SPEAKER_15]: I think this may be a reference to the morning after the morning after our baby was born, which perhaps wasn't the most adept time for me to hold a 7.30 in the morning press conference.

39
00:03:07,444 --> 00:03:08,826
[SPEAKER_15]: But I can give you the position...

40
00:03:08,846 --> 00:03:11,168
[SPEAKER_15]: The Prime Minister had a baby when he was Prime Minister.

41
00:03:11,188 --> 00:03:13,611
[SPEAKER_30]: Gordon Brown had a baby when he was Chancellor of the Exchequer.

42
00:03:13,631 --> 00:03:14,552
[SPEAKER_15]: They didn't freak out.

43
00:03:14,532 --> 00:03:18,538
[SPEAKER_15]: No, but they didn't launch a national election campaign 36 hours later either.

44
00:03:18,578 --> 00:03:22,764
[SPEAKER_15]: They had a more decent period of paternity leave than was available to me, unfortunately.

45
00:03:23,125 --> 00:03:32,598
[SPEAKER_15]: However, what we're basically saying in this campaign as Liberal Democrats, we want a fair tax system and we want the proceeds of that tax applied fairly in the country.

46
00:03:33,039 --> 00:03:37,806
[SPEAKER_15]: We're saying that if you want to get rid of student top-up fees and tuition fees,

47
00:03:37,786 --> 00:03:55,761
[SPEAKER_15]: If you want older people to enjoy free long-term care if they are suffering from Alzheimer's or Parkinson's with washing, feeding or dressing, and if you want to put money in to get rid of the council tax and replace it with a fair system of local tax based on people's ability to pay,

48
00:03:55,741 --> 00:04:08,120
[SPEAKER_15]: a 1% number of people, the 1% top income taxpayers, to achieve all those things, they would see their top rate of tax go up to 50p for every pound above £100,000 income.

49
00:04:08,501 --> 00:04:10,704
[SPEAKER_15]: That's still less than the same people were paying.

50
00:04:11,065 --> 00:04:17,195
[SPEAKER_15]: For most of the period, Mrs Thatcher was Prime Minister and the top rate of taxpayers felt they had quite a good deal with her.

51
00:04:17,435 --> 00:04:19,779
[SPEAKER_15]: James Gray, does that explain it?

52
00:04:20,119 --> 00:04:21,061
[SPEAKER_37]: Yeah, I think so.

53
00:04:21,081 --> 00:04:22,002
[SPEAKER_36]: You, sir, yeah?

54
00:04:22,538 --> 00:04:26,035
[SPEAKER_36]: And are you worried that the local income tax...

55
00:04:26,302 --> 00:04:37,779
[SPEAKER_36]: which will affect people who earn roughly more than £40,000, as I understand it, will take away potential sort of middle-class voters from the Conservatives to vote for you, and they'll obviously decide they don't want to do that.

56
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:44,168
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, if you have a household income in the region of £42,000, when you begin to get above that, you will pay more.

57
00:04:44,208 --> 00:04:49,196
[SPEAKER_15]: That's about a quarter of people in this country do pay more under our local tax proposals.

58
00:04:49,717 --> 00:04:56,106
[SPEAKER_15]: But the Institute of Fiscal Studies today has been looking at all three parties, their views on these and other matters.

59
00:04:56,086 --> 00:05:01,011
[SPEAKER_15]: They say that 70% of people will benefit from our local income tax proposals.

60
00:05:01,412 --> 00:05:04,375
[SPEAKER_15]: The big winners, let's be honest about this, will be pensioners.

61
00:05:04,435 --> 00:05:08,079
[SPEAKER_15]: Six million pensioners will be taken out of local tax altogether.

62
00:05:08,379 --> 00:05:11,543
[SPEAKER_15]: But there will be losers, and we've been quite honest with people.

63
00:05:12,023 --> 00:05:19,992
[SPEAKER_15]: You've got two parties on offer at this election, Labour and Conservative, applying different forms of sticking plaster to council tax.

64
00:05:20,573 --> 00:05:22,735
[SPEAKER_15]: We say you've got to do something about the wound.

65
00:05:22,715 --> 00:05:23,777
[SPEAKER_15]: you've got to heal the wound.

66
00:05:24,117 --> 00:05:30,488
[SPEAKER_15]: And at least we've been honest enough, and I think brave enough, to come forward with a new local tax proposal.

67
00:05:30,668 --> 00:05:41,026
[SPEAKER_15]: We argue it's favour, it's fairer, but we don't try and pretend, whatever system you have, that some people will be better off as a result, others will be worse off, but the vast majority will be better off.

68
00:05:41,046 --> 00:05:44,672
[SPEAKER_30]: But you hit people on modest incomes, couples on modest incomes, quite hard.

69
00:05:44,652 --> 00:05:47,636
[SPEAKER_30]: The average... Is it a way to go into an election?

70
00:05:47,656 --> 00:05:50,019
[SPEAKER_30]: 25% of the population are going to pay more tax?

71
00:05:50,039 --> 00:05:53,283
[SPEAKER_15]: 75% unaffected or better off.

72
00:05:53,363 --> 00:05:55,265
[SPEAKER_15]: But do remember, it is part of the package.

73
00:05:55,465 --> 00:06:07,119
[SPEAKER_15]: It is also related, going back to the first question, to what many of those households also gain in terms of if they have students at university, no fees, if they have elderly parents, help that is not available at the moment.

74
00:06:07,260 --> 00:06:08,181
[SPEAKER_15]: It is a deal.

75
00:06:08,201 --> 00:06:10,103
[SPEAKER_15]: The lady with spectacles.

76
00:06:10,623 --> 00:06:17,493
[SPEAKER_07]: If you went onto your website and I worked out, in my area, a Band D property, double income, would be £33,000.

77
00:06:17,814 --> 00:06:19,937
[SPEAKER_07]: You've only got to earn that and then you would pay more.

78
00:06:20,298 --> 00:06:24,464
[SPEAKER_07]: That is not a lot of money in the South East when you're already saddled with high mortgages.

79
00:06:24,924 --> 00:06:31,815
[SPEAKER_15]: No, as I say, the typical figure...

80
00:06:31,835 --> 00:06:34,639
[SPEAKER_07]: APPLAUSE ..£33,000 is an awful lot less than £42,000.

81
00:06:34,872 --> 00:06:40,797
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, 42 is the typical figure for across the country as a whole, and this has been looked at by outside experts.

82
00:06:40,817 --> 00:06:42,038
[SPEAKER_30]: But what about in the South East?

83
00:06:42,138 --> 00:06:46,002
[SPEAKER_30]: The ladies from the South East, the economics of the South East are different.

84
00:06:46,222 --> 00:06:48,484
[SPEAKER_30]: What percentage of people in the South East will pay higher tax?

85
00:06:48,504 --> 00:06:50,546
[SPEAKER_15]: It varies from one local authority area to another.

86
00:06:50,566 --> 00:06:53,308
[SPEAKER_15]: Of course, but on average in the South East as a whole?

87
00:06:53,328 --> 00:06:59,354
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, the average figure for the country as a whole is £450 savings per household.

88
00:06:59,374 --> 00:07:00,975
[SPEAKER_15]: But you're right to look at our website.

89
00:07:00,995 --> 00:07:04,238
[SPEAKER_15]: That's why we've made all this available, and I'd encourage people to watch it.

90
00:07:04,218 --> 00:07:04,679
[SPEAKER_15]: Mr. Kennedy.

91
00:07:04,699 --> 00:07:05,160
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, I do.

92
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:05,922
[SPEAKER_15]: Let's make your point again.

93
00:07:05,942 --> 00:07:10,492
[SPEAKER_07]: Ordinary families are going to have to pay a lot more, and that's an awful lot more families than you're saying.

94
00:07:10,692 --> 00:07:12,817
[SPEAKER_15]: No, it's a quarter of households.

95
00:07:12,857 --> 00:07:14,180
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, that is the official figure.

96
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:17,667
[SPEAKER_07]: In the whole country, if you're in the Outer Hebrides, I can believe you probably pay less.

97
00:07:18,208 --> 00:07:19,130
[SPEAKER_15]: No, it's not.

98
00:07:19,150 --> 00:07:21,315
[SPEAKER_15]: Have you worked out the geographical effect of this, Mr. Kennedy?

99
00:07:21,295 --> 00:07:23,778
[SPEAKER_15]: It's all detailed on the website.

100
00:07:24,238 --> 00:07:25,260
[SPEAKER_15]: Can you give me the answer?

101
00:07:25,280 --> 00:07:31,206
[SPEAKER_15]: I have the south-east income figure for you, which is the one you can base it on.

102
00:07:31,267 --> 00:07:35,311
[SPEAKER_15]: The average salary in the south-east is an awful lot lower than people imagine.

103
00:07:35,411 --> 00:07:37,454
[SPEAKER_15]: It's £27,000 a year.

104
00:07:37,874 --> 00:07:38,735
[SPEAKER_15]: The woman here.

105
00:07:38,755 --> 00:07:49,007
[SPEAKER_23]: By charging a higher rate of income tax on higher salaries,

106
00:07:50,776 --> 00:07:51,257
[SPEAKER_30]: No?

107
00:07:51,277 --> 00:07:51,657
[SPEAKER_30]: Done?

108
00:07:51,797 --> 00:07:52,599
[SPEAKER_30]: OK, come to you instead.

109
00:07:53,039 --> 00:07:53,680
[SPEAKER_30]: Come back to you later.

110
00:07:53,921 --> 00:07:58,347
[SPEAKER_05]: Keeping with the theme you started off with, congratulations, you've just had your first child.

111
00:07:58,427 --> 00:07:59,048
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

112
00:07:59,068 --> 00:08:09,463
[SPEAKER_05]: Are you aware that a CBBC survey of children found that 95% of them state that they've suffered bullying in our school system?

113
00:08:10,044 --> 00:08:14,691
[SPEAKER_05]: And would you support the idea of a national anti-bullying centre for children?

114
00:08:14,992 --> 00:08:16,394
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, that's a different question.

115
00:08:16,414 --> 00:08:17,295
[SPEAKER_30]: Do you want to answer that briefly?

116
00:08:17,336 --> 00:08:20,020
[SPEAKER_15]: What I'd say, the bullying problem is a terrible problem.

117
00:08:20,280 --> 00:08:22,103
[SPEAKER_15]: You need more playground supervision.

118
00:08:22,503 --> 00:08:24,346
[SPEAKER_15]: You need more involvement of the parents.

119
00:08:24,787 --> 00:08:28,873
[SPEAKER_05]: I think there's no compulsory set-up inside our school system.

120
00:08:29,153 --> 00:08:30,255
[SPEAKER_05]: It's left down to the heads.

121
00:08:30,275 --> 00:08:33,921
[SPEAKER_30]: Hold on, let's not go to that, because I want to stick on the question you were asked originally.

122
00:08:34,001 --> 00:08:35,122
[SPEAKER_30]: Anybody else got a point on that?

123
00:08:35,143 --> 00:08:36,465
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes, the woman there.

124
00:08:37,045 --> 00:08:43,395
[SPEAKER_38]: Do you think another percentage tax on our earnings could possibly put people off earning a higher salary?

125
00:08:43,882 --> 00:08:45,844
[SPEAKER_15]: No, I don't think it will, in all honesty.

126
00:08:45,905 --> 00:08:54,896
[SPEAKER_15]: Nobody's talking about a return to the days in the 1970s in this country when the top income earners were on 90 plus, 95% plus levels of tax.

127
00:08:54,916 --> 00:08:55,637
[SPEAKER_15]: That was crazy.

128
00:08:55,657 --> 00:08:59,181
[SPEAKER_15]: That caused a brain drain, a loss of talent and money to the country.

129
00:08:59,642 --> 00:09:06,430
[SPEAKER_15]: And do remember that the people you're talking about here, those top rate taxpayers, 1% of people,

130
00:09:06,410 --> 00:09:09,055
[SPEAKER_15]: They've got children that they want to put through university.

131
00:09:09,215 --> 00:09:11,420
[SPEAKER_15]: They've got elderly parents that they're caring about.

132
00:09:12,121 --> 00:09:16,069
[SPEAKER_15]: They benefit from the wider policies that we're putting forward.

133
00:09:16,089 --> 00:09:17,592
[SPEAKER_15]: So I think it's a fairer system.

134
00:09:17,812 --> 00:09:22,782
[SPEAKER_15]: There must be something wrong, surely, that after eight years of a Labour government, and let's face it,

135
00:09:22,762 --> 00:09:26,388
[SPEAKER_15]: They've had a pretty benign economic backdrop over those eight years.

136
00:09:26,849 --> 00:09:38,730
[SPEAKER_15]: The poorest people in our society, with direct and indirect tax, now pay, still pay, a higher proportion of their household income in tax than do the very top earners.

137
00:09:39,031 --> 00:09:42,597
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, I don't think that's a fair society.

138
00:09:42,617 --> 00:09:42,677
OK.

139
00:09:44,969 --> 00:09:46,194
[SPEAKER_30]: We'll move on to another question.

140
00:09:46,214 --> 00:09:47,982
[SPEAKER_30]: Daniel Shaik, please.

141
00:09:48,464 --> 00:09:49,146
[SPEAKER_30]: Daniel Shaik.

142
00:09:49,930 --> 00:09:54,810
[SPEAKER_12]: If you were to go ahead with plans to withdraw British troops from Iraq, how would you guarantee the security of Iraqis?

143
00:09:55,297 --> 00:09:57,179
[SPEAKER_15]: First of all, yes, we are the only party...

144
00:09:57,480 --> 00:09:59,422
[SPEAKER_15]: Your plan is to move out by Christmas?

145
00:09:59,462 --> 00:09:59,882
[SPEAKER_15]: That's right.

146
00:10:00,143 --> 00:10:06,190
[SPEAKER_15]: The UN mandate, the current United Nations mandate for the occupying forces expires at the end of this calendar year.

147
00:10:06,210 --> 00:10:14,399
[SPEAKER_15]: And we have argued, we're the only party arguing this, obviously in the election, that we believe there should now be a phased withdrawal of British troops with that deadline in mind.

148
00:10:14,980 --> 00:10:20,106
[SPEAKER_15]: I think, obviously, we profoundly disagreed with the decision to go to war in Iraq.

149
00:10:20,266 --> 00:10:21,667
[SPEAKER_15]: And I think everybody knows that.

150
00:10:21,687 --> 00:10:23,970
[SPEAKER_15]: We were the only party that opposed it in Parliament.

151
00:10:23,950 --> 00:10:25,092
[SPEAKER_15]: We are where we are.

152
00:10:25,592 --> 00:10:31,039
[SPEAKER_15]: We have got 8,000 British service personnel still out there in Iraq.

153
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:35,365
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'll tell you what made me angry today, because this issue has been, as you know, in the headlines.

154
00:10:35,786 --> 00:10:47,882
[SPEAKER_15]: When the Prime Minister said this morning that the published advice of the Attorney General, which had to be absolutely dragged from him, we've been calling for this for the last year and a half, represented a damp squib.

155
00:10:47,862 --> 00:10:58,665
[SPEAKER_15]: I say to Tony Blair, go and describe these findings as a damp squib to the families of the British service personnel who gave their lives in Iraq, and to the innocent Iraqi citizens who were killed.

156
00:11:03,657 --> 00:11:10,167
[SPEAKER_30]: The question was how you would guarantee the security of the Iraqis if the elected Iraqi government asked British troops to stay.

157
00:11:10,828 --> 00:11:15,414
[SPEAKER_30]: Would you pull them out and say, to hell, we are not interested, wash our hands of all this?

158
00:11:15,434 --> 00:11:24,788
[SPEAKER_15]: I am afraid that amongst the many principled arguments we put forward against the war, it was the fact that one sovereign country, without international

159
00:11:24,768 --> 00:11:30,016
[SPEAKER_15]: mandate could go and invade another sovereign country and regime change that sovereign country.

160
00:11:30,036 --> 00:11:33,301
[SPEAKER_15]: We're all pleased to see the back of Saddam, but this was never the way to go about it.

161
00:11:33,701 --> 00:11:50,126
[SPEAKER_15]: Therefore, it is becoming a sovereign state, it has the right to take its own decisions, and I personally now don't believe, nearly two years and more after the event, that the continuing presence of occupying troops offers the Iraqis a better long-term solution.

162
00:11:50,366 --> 00:11:51,568
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we should come home.

163
00:11:51,548 --> 00:11:53,511
[SPEAKER_30]: Of course, Saddam would still be there if you had your way.

164
00:11:53,531 --> 00:11:54,572
[SPEAKER_15]: Not necessarily so.

165
00:11:54,612 --> 00:12:16,099
[SPEAKER_15]: The Iraq survey group said, when they looked at the country at the time, that the military, the ethnic breakdown, and the financial circumstances or such, that had he been exposed, had the weapons inspectors been given time, and we'd found out, in Iraq and outside Iraq, he didn't have weapons of mass destruction, his biggest club to maintain his power base would have been gone.

166
00:12:16,380 --> 00:12:17,401
[SPEAKER_15]: That's the tragedy of the situation.

167
00:12:17,421 --> 00:12:17,902
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you believe that?

168
00:12:17,922 --> 00:12:18,923
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you believe he'd have gone?

169
00:12:18,903 --> 00:12:25,517
[SPEAKER_15]: I think the Iraq survey group, who are closer to this than any of us, said that the conditions were there for an implosion of the regime.

170
00:12:25,737 --> 00:12:26,920
[SPEAKER_15]: The woman at the back.

171
00:12:26,940 --> 00:12:28,403
[SPEAKER_16]: You talked about sovereignty.

172
00:12:28,423 --> 00:12:29,886
[SPEAKER_16]: Do you think sovereignty is absolute?

173
00:12:30,427 --> 00:12:35,578
[SPEAKER_16]: Do you think whatever someone does to their own people, they're allowed to do that?

174
00:12:35,558 --> 00:12:41,765
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I think that under the United Nations Charter, if our country is attacked by another country, we have a right to defend ourselves.

175
00:12:42,045 --> 00:12:49,414
[SPEAKER_15]: What we don't have a right to do under the United Nations Charter is simply, without UN authority, go into another country and change its government.

176
00:12:49,634 --> 00:12:54,179
[SPEAKER_15]: Because if we didn't like governments, and there's many around the world we don't do, where do you stop?

177
00:12:54,520 --> 00:12:59,625
[SPEAKER_15]: Are we going to start a war in Zimbabwe, for example, because Mugabe is a murderous dictator?

178
00:12:59,926 --> 00:13:01,588
[SPEAKER_15]: Are we going to invade North Korea?

179
00:13:02,048 --> 00:13:02,969
[SPEAKER_15]: Where does it stop?

180
00:13:03,069 --> 00:13:04,671
[SPEAKER_15]: The world order breaks down.

181
00:13:06,035 --> 00:13:11,877
[SPEAKER_30]: We went into Kosovo.

182
00:13:12,515 --> 00:13:14,577
[SPEAKER_15]: We did, but there was... And you supported that?

183
00:13:14,597 --> 00:13:16,579
[SPEAKER_15]: We did support the entry into Kosovo.

184
00:13:16,659 --> 00:13:17,960
[SPEAKER_15]: Isn't that an illogical position?

185
00:13:17,980 --> 00:13:20,662
[SPEAKER_15]: No, we supported the government's action over Afghanistan.

186
00:13:20,983 --> 00:13:23,665
[SPEAKER_15]: We're not viewing this from some...

187
00:13:23,685 --> 00:13:25,527
[SPEAKER_30]: But you said without the United Nations agreement.

188
00:13:25,547 --> 00:13:26,768
[SPEAKER_30]: There was no United Nations agreement in Kosovo.

189
00:13:26,788 --> 00:13:32,473
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, the issue about Kosovo was the position of the Russians at the time, and although the Russians couldn't bring themselves to vote for that...

190
00:13:32,493 --> 00:13:34,635
[SPEAKER_30]: The position of the French on Iraq, exactly the same.

191
00:13:34,655 --> 00:13:35,215
[SPEAKER_15]: What's the difference?

192
00:13:35,235 --> 00:13:41,781
[SPEAKER_15]: No, the position was not the same, because the international community was so shattered, not just at Security Council level, but within the UN generally.

193
00:13:41,841 --> 00:13:42,522
[SPEAKER_15]: OK, you, sir.

194
00:13:42,502 --> 00:13:51,273
[SPEAKER_33]: So, you're honestly saying that if the Iraqi government come to you at Christmas and say, we need British troops to stay in Iraq, you will just disregard what they say and pull them out?

195
00:13:51,293 --> 00:14:00,885
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm afraid to say I think the responsibility for a British government at this stage, two years after the event, with the loss of life we've suffered, with the amount of innocent civilians in Iraq, that we have been...

196
00:14:00,905 --> 00:14:04,429
[SPEAKER_33]: But surely more innocent civilians will die if you pull the troops out.

197
00:14:04,709 --> 00:14:06,832
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, we don't even...

198
00:14:07,272 --> 00:14:07,733
[SPEAKER_15]: I have to say to you...

199
00:14:09,603 --> 00:14:22,085
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't think that will be the case because I think that the occupying troops, the Americans more than the British it has to be said, but the very presence of occupying troops is acting as a force for the insurrectionists within Iraq.

200
00:14:22,306 --> 00:14:34,227
[SPEAKER_15]: But do remember when you say, wouldn't more Iraqis died, we can't even turn round as a country and say how many innocent Iraqis did die because we've never bothered to do the body count.

201
00:14:34,207 --> 00:14:48,790
[SPEAKER_15]: When I say not in my name, Mr Blair, it's not just that I disagreed with the government on the policy, I'm ashamed of what the government did in the name of our country.

202
00:14:50,288 --> 00:14:54,112
[SPEAKER_34]: I do actually agree with you, but what if the UN want people in there?

203
00:14:54,373 --> 00:14:55,034
[SPEAKER_34]: What are you going to do then?

204
00:14:55,054 --> 00:14:56,415
[SPEAKER_34]: Are you going to refuse with the UN?

205
00:14:56,736 --> 00:14:58,157
[SPEAKER_15]: No, not necessarily so.

206
00:14:58,458 --> 00:15:04,665
[SPEAKER_15]: If there's an international consensus which involves the United Nations, then of course that changes the whole picture at the moment.

207
00:15:04,945 --> 00:15:10,472
[SPEAKER_15]: But at the moment, the UN mandate for those occupying forces expires at the end of this year.

208
00:15:10,772 --> 00:15:13,335
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, nobody knows at this stage whether it will be renewed or extended.

209
00:15:13,355 --> 00:15:14,777
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, but what if they want peacekeepers in?

210
00:15:14,977 --> 00:15:16,198
[SPEAKER_15]: We can't answer that.

211
00:15:16,218 --> 00:15:19,502
[SPEAKER_15]: Therefore, we should be working responsibly to bring our forces home.

212
00:15:19,482 --> 00:15:23,068
[SPEAKER_34]: I'm talking about peacekeepers, it's a different thing.

213
00:15:23,088 --> 00:15:23,969
[SPEAKER_15]: That's different completely.

214
00:15:23,989 --> 00:15:42,179
[SPEAKER_15]: We've always said that actually, instead of having the flag of the United States flying in so much of Iraq, have the flag of the United Nations and have forces particularly drawn from other countries, other than our own and the United States, Muslim forces in particular, from other countries in Iraq.

215
00:15:42,199 --> 00:15:44,342
[SPEAKER_30]: But not British even wearing blue helmets?

216
00:15:44,322 --> 00:15:46,808
[SPEAKER_15]: British by all means wearing blue helmets.

217
00:15:46,828 --> 00:15:47,850
[SPEAKER_15]: That's a very different commitment.

218
00:15:47,870 --> 00:15:49,654
[SPEAKER_30]: The man up there and then I'll come to you.

219
00:15:49,775 --> 00:15:55,328
[SPEAKER_42]: If you win the election and George Bush says to you, let's go to war again without the authority of the UN, you will definitely say no?

220
00:15:55,608 --> 00:15:55,989
[SPEAKER_15]: Correct.

221
00:15:56,350 --> 00:15:57,994
[SPEAKER_15]: And I've said that to George.

222
00:15:58,413 --> 00:16:14,363
[SPEAKER_15]: and what's more President Bush knows that because when I met him in London during a state visit a year and a half ago we had this very discussion and I confirmed that was a view and interestingly although we disagreed

223
00:16:14,343 --> 00:16:25,541
[SPEAKER_15]: Rather revealingly, he remarked to me during that discussion that he'd enjoyed it, although he didn't see eye to eye on Iraq, because, as he put it, you're one of the few guys I'm meeting on this visit that actually doesn't agree with me.

224
00:16:25,581 --> 00:16:29,668
[SPEAKER_15]: He was only allowed to meet people that were singing from his hymn sheet.

225
00:16:29,688 --> 00:16:30,529
[SPEAKER_15]: OK. You, sir.

226
00:16:30,678 --> 00:16:38,549
[SPEAKER_18]: As Mr Kennedy frequently says, the Liberal Democrats were the only party to take a stance against the war, which I was an advocate of.

227
00:16:38,930 --> 00:16:42,095
[SPEAKER_18]: Do you feel that you've made enough political capital out of that view?

228
00:16:42,115 --> 00:16:45,720
[SPEAKER_18]: Because when I look at the opinion polls, I quite frankly don't see them changing.

229
00:16:45,760 --> 00:16:47,482
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't see that it's made an impact.

230
00:16:47,502 --> 00:16:54,933
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't see that the public have realised that the Liberal Democrats were on the majority of the public side, yet they don't seem to be voting for you.

231
00:16:54,953 --> 00:17:00,381
[SPEAKER_18]: Do you think that reflects, to a certain extent, the lack of charisma and dynamism you show as a leader?

232
00:17:00,361 --> 00:17:06,675
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I think that if you look at the level of support... That's all right.

233
00:17:06,695 --> 00:17:09,421
[SPEAKER_15]: You're being much more generous than Michael Howard is about Tony Blair.

234
00:17:10,543 --> 00:17:12,588
[SPEAKER_15]: That's not an insult at all, I can assure you.

235
00:17:13,510 --> 00:17:17,639
[SPEAKER_15]: I think, first of all, if you look at the level of support for the Liberal Democrats, it was a distinctive position.

236
00:17:17,739 --> 00:17:19,062
[SPEAKER_15]: It was taken on principle.

237
00:17:19,042 --> 00:17:36,683
[SPEAKER_15]: and people forget two years on, it was actually quite courageous because popular opinion at that point amongst commentators, political opponents, I was being called Charlie Chamberlain in the House of Commons by Conservatives, betraying a distinct lack of knowledge of history of their own party, incidentally.

238
00:17:37,003 --> 00:17:38,084
[SPEAKER_15]: But we took the stand.

239
00:17:38,705 --> 00:17:40,968
[SPEAKER_15]: Labour support has gone down over Iraq.

240
00:17:41,248 --> 00:17:42,870
[SPEAKER_15]: That support is transferred to us.

241
00:17:43,250 --> 00:17:44,712
[SPEAKER_15]: And in this campaign, sir,

242
00:17:44,692 --> 00:17:49,725
[SPEAKER_15]: We went in at our highest ever level for an election campaign that we've ever fought as a party.

243
00:17:50,106 --> 00:17:53,795
[SPEAKER_15]: And as we speak tonight, we're at a higher level than we've ever achieved.

244
00:17:53,875 --> 00:17:54,938
[SPEAKER_15]: And we're moving up.

245
00:17:56,015 --> 00:18:02,863
[SPEAKER_18]: that you have any opportunity, no matter what anyone claims, that you'll be the real alternative or even, in fact, the national opposition.

246
00:18:03,164 --> 00:18:04,685
[SPEAKER_18]: It's just absolute rubbish.

247
00:18:04,705 --> 00:18:08,590
[SPEAKER_15]: With a week to go, let's see what's going to happen.

248
00:18:08,630 --> 00:18:14,097
[SPEAKER_15]: The one thing people have concluded so far in the campaign is the Conservatives can't win this election.

249
00:18:14,517 --> 00:18:18,322
[SPEAKER_15]: They don't like the idea of Tony Blair back with another three-figure majority.

250
00:18:18,702 --> 00:18:21,846
[SPEAKER_15]: Therefore, what are they going to make their minds up over these next few days?

251
00:18:22,287 --> 00:18:25,971
[SPEAKER_15]: Increasingly, they are looking at us, and it's up to us to make the case.

252
00:18:26,221 --> 00:18:28,165
[SPEAKER_30]: The man there.

253
00:18:28,345 --> 00:18:32,994
[SPEAKER_32]: If there was a hung Parliament and you were offered a coalition... We'll come to that later on, I think.

254
00:18:33,175 --> 00:18:34,557
[SPEAKER_32]: It's about this issue.

255
00:18:34,697 --> 00:18:35,719
[SPEAKER_30]: Can we just hold it?

256
00:18:36,020 --> 00:18:39,407
[SPEAKER_30]: We've got a question about that and I don't want him to go off on that at the moment.

257
00:18:39,487 --> 00:18:40,970
[SPEAKER_30]: You, madam, over there, and then we'll move on.

258
00:18:41,150 --> 00:18:43,234
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes.

259
00:18:43,214 --> 00:18:57,247
[SPEAKER_02]: You mentioned Mr. Bush, and given that you differ on a number of issues with him, you have different views on a number of key issues.

260
00:18:57,769 --> 00:19:01,678
[SPEAKER_02]: So how would that impact relations between Britain and the U.S. if you were to be

261
00:19:01,658 --> 00:19:20,463
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't think that is... Whatever the outcome of our election here, it would be no different from when President Bush defeated Vice President Gore, and you went from a Democrat administration that Prime Minister Blair was very close to, to a Republican one, which at that point we all thought he'd be much further away from.

262
00:19:20,503 --> 00:19:23,127
[SPEAKER_15]: How wrong you can be in your historical judgements.

263
00:19:23,107 --> 00:19:28,033
[SPEAKER_15]: But no, I think we respect our democratic traditions on both sides of the Atlantic.

264
00:19:28,053 --> 00:19:30,896
[SPEAKER_15]: And remember, this is not about anti-Americanism on our part.

265
00:19:30,917 --> 00:19:34,160
[SPEAKER_15]: I had one of the happiest years of my life as a student in the United States.

266
00:19:34,481 --> 00:19:41,389
[SPEAKER_15]: This is about disagreement with an American administration, which, remember, half the citizens of America don't agree with either.

267
00:19:41,710 --> 00:19:42,030
[SPEAKER_15]: All right?

268
00:19:42,050 --> 00:19:43,091
[SPEAKER_15]: Lauren Cox, please.

269
00:19:43,171 --> 00:19:44,473
[SPEAKER_15]: Question from Lauren Cox.

270
00:19:44,825 --> 00:19:52,273
[SPEAKER_17]: what's your views on claims that your policies of free long-term health care for the elderly and abolishing tuition fees are pandering to the middle classes?

271
00:19:52,493 --> 00:20:13,414
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, my view about this is that if you're running a fair society in this country, and if you are taxing that very small percentage at the wealthiest end that bit more, the way in which we achieve a sense that we're in it together in this country, whatever our income or backgrounds or aspirations, is that you spread the benefits right across the board.

272
00:20:13,394 --> 00:20:17,663
[SPEAKER_15]: somebody kindly mentioned about us becoming a family within the last couple of weeks.

273
00:20:17,683 --> 00:20:26,501
[SPEAKER_15]: Now my wife and myself are lucky in the sense that academically we got the opportunity to go to university and we got degrees and that's helped both our lives and careers subsequently.

274
00:20:26,862 --> 00:20:29,547
[SPEAKER_15]: But that same night in that same hospital

275
00:20:29,527 --> 00:20:46,724
[SPEAKER_15]: There were people without, perhaps, university degrees, perhaps not aspiring ever from their backgrounds to have had that opportunity, but they benefit, just as we did, from the clinicians, the consultants, the doctors that, as a society, we've invested in to give that knowledge and that skill base.

276
00:20:46,744 --> 00:20:55,874
[SPEAKER_30]: But isn't Lauren Cox's point that these things are, at present, means-tested, and by making them a universal benefit, you're helping people who can actually afford to pay something towards them.

277
00:20:55,894 --> 00:20:56,755
[SPEAKER_30]: They suddenly won't have to.

278
00:20:56,795 --> 00:20:58,116
[SPEAKER_30]: Is that your point, Lauren?

279
00:20:58,096 --> 00:20:58,837
[SPEAKER_17]: partly.

280
00:20:59,578 --> 00:21:09,469
[SPEAKER_17]: It depends on whether you think that both of those aims could actually be achieved solely by the 50% tax.

281
00:21:09,509 --> 00:21:10,390
[SPEAKER_15]: The figures add up.

282
00:21:10,911 --> 00:21:17,498
[SPEAKER_15]: Tony Blair might disagree with me as he does regularly in the House of Commons about the policy and he is doing something different.

283
00:21:17,578 --> 00:21:20,762
[SPEAKER_15]: What cannot be denied is that the money that comes in

284
00:21:20,742 --> 00:21:24,089
[SPEAKER_15]: more than makes up the money that would go out for those policies.

285
00:21:24,149 --> 00:21:39,983
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, I think it's fairer to treat society on an equal basis, because if we go down the other route, as we are at the moment with pensions, say, more and more means testing, more complexity, more pensioners in genuine need who don't actually get the support that is there for them.

286
00:21:39,963 --> 00:21:55,085
[SPEAKER_15]: Or, worse still, you have an increasingly divided society, where those of us who are that bit better off can increasingly opt towards private provision, and those who are less well off are dependent on a shrinking quality of state support.

287
00:21:55,386 --> 00:21:58,010
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, that is not in any of our long-term interests.

288
00:21:58,070 --> 00:22:00,974
[SPEAKER_30]: But you said in Scotland you were going to abolish these fees, didn't you?

289
00:22:01,074 --> 00:22:01,274
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes.

290
00:22:01,715 --> 00:22:02,376
[SPEAKER_15]: What happened?

291
00:22:02,474 --> 00:22:03,616
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, we abolished the fees.

292
00:22:03,636 --> 00:22:05,278
[SPEAKER_15]: You don't pay for tuition in Scotland.

293
00:22:05,379 --> 00:22:06,260
[SPEAKER_15]: And what happens now?

294
00:22:06,621 --> 00:22:10,206
[SPEAKER_15]: And what happens now is that the rate of application from Scots...

295
00:22:10,226 --> 00:22:10,747
[SPEAKER_15]: Hang on, hang on.

296
00:22:10,767 --> 00:22:11,829
[SPEAKER_15]: What happens financially now?

297
00:22:11,849 --> 00:22:12,129
[SPEAKER_30]: Oh, I see.

298
00:22:12,149 --> 00:22:13,992
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, what happens... Everybody pays... No.

299
00:22:14,093 --> 00:22:15,154
[SPEAKER_30]: ..£2,000.

300
00:22:15,355 --> 00:22:16,837
[SPEAKER_15]: You only pay... Graduate tax.

301
00:22:16,857 --> 00:22:18,940
[SPEAKER_15]: It's not a graduate tax, and let me explain why.

302
00:22:18,980 --> 00:22:20,202
[SPEAKER_15]: Let me be quite clear about this.

303
00:22:20,643 --> 00:22:25,090
[SPEAKER_15]: Once your income, beyond graduation, goes above a certain level,

304
00:22:25,070 --> 00:22:33,782
[SPEAKER_15]: you have a £2,000 which kicks in to pay, not for the tuition you received, but it sets up an endowment fund of new money.

305
00:22:33,822 --> 00:22:35,965
[SPEAKER_15]: What's the difference between that and top-up fees or tuition fees?

306
00:22:35,985 --> 00:22:36,987
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll tell you what the difference is.

307
00:22:37,107 --> 00:22:38,329
[SPEAKER_15]: From the point of view of the person who's paying it?

308
00:22:38,349 --> 00:22:41,032
[SPEAKER_15]: If you allow me to answer the question, David, I'll tell you exactly what the difference is.

309
00:22:41,313 --> 00:22:42,094
[SPEAKER_15]: The difference is this.

310
00:22:42,474 --> 00:22:46,540
[SPEAKER_15]: The money doesn't go to the Scottish universities for their tuition costs.

311
00:22:46,861 --> 00:22:54,992
[SPEAKER_15]: It goes to an endowment fund which enables students or potential students from poorer Scottish backgrounds to get the chance to go to university in the first place.

312
00:22:54,972 --> 00:22:56,815
[SPEAKER_15]: I think that's a reasonable payback.

313
00:22:56,835 --> 00:22:57,896
[SPEAKER_30]: Sorry, let's just get this straight.

314
00:22:57,936 --> 00:23:03,684
[SPEAKER_30]: The very poorest still now pay £2,000, whereas before means-tested they'd have paid nothing.

315
00:23:04,365 --> 00:23:05,166
[SPEAKER_15]: Is that true or not?

316
00:23:05,266 --> 00:23:06,208
[SPEAKER_15]: No, it's not true.

317
00:23:06,228 --> 00:23:16,322
[SPEAKER_15]: What we're saying is that if you get your degree, you graduate, you go into the labour market, once you're above a certain level of income, you have a £2,000 contribution to make.

318
00:23:16,302 --> 00:23:18,566
[SPEAKER_15]: over phased installments.

319
00:23:19,007 --> 00:23:27,542
[SPEAKER_15]: That money sets up an endowment fund, it doesn't go to the universities, and it goes to widen the net of poorer students who can come in as the next generation of students.

320
00:23:27,862 --> 00:23:28,644
[SPEAKER_15]: Now I think that's good.

321
00:23:28,884 --> 00:23:33,151
[SPEAKER_15]: And can I come back to what the lady who asked me the question was pointing out about this?

322
00:23:33,492 --> 00:23:34,654
[SPEAKER_15]: What has been the implication?

323
00:23:34,975 --> 00:23:39,222
[SPEAKER_15]: The implication in Scotland, the subsequent events have shown,

324
00:23:39,202 --> 00:23:52,255
[SPEAKER_15]: that the rate of increase of application for Scots wanting to go to Scottish universities is now significantly higher than it is in England and Wales for English and Welsh students wanting to go to English and Welsh universities.

325
00:23:52,275 --> 00:24:02,225
[SPEAKER_15]: And you can't tell me that isn't because people look at the appalling prospect of £12,000, £20,000 worth of debt and say, I can't afford it, my family can't afford it.

326
00:24:02,245 --> 00:24:02,945
[SPEAKER_15]: That's terrible.

327
00:24:02,965 --> 00:24:04,947
[SPEAKER_30]: That's absolutely terrible.

328
00:24:04,967 --> 00:24:05,648
[SPEAKER_30]: Let's move on.

329
00:24:06,725 --> 00:24:09,343
[SPEAKER_30]: Christian, Christian Sanderson, please.

330
00:24:09,509 --> 00:24:16,539
[SPEAKER_19]: If there were to be a hung Parliament next week, would the Liberal Democrats be prepared to go into a coalition with Labour?

331
00:24:16,979 --> 00:24:17,059
[SPEAKER_19]: No.

332
00:24:17,139 --> 00:24:18,622
[SPEAKER_19]: And would they support Tony Blair?

333
00:24:18,642 --> 00:24:18,822
[SPEAKER_19]: No.

334
00:24:19,022 --> 00:24:20,945
[SPEAKER_19]: OK, you've answered my question.

335
00:24:20,965 --> 00:24:21,025
[SPEAKER_30]: No.

336
00:24:21,045 --> 00:24:21,365
[SPEAKER_30]: Hang on.

337
00:24:21,385 --> 00:24:22,767
[SPEAKER_30]: No, there are two questions.

338
00:24:23,088 --> 00:24:25,010
[SPEAKER_30]: The first question was, would you go into a coalition?

339
00:24:25,050 --> 00:24:26,693
[SPEAKER_30]: The second part was...

340
00:24:26,713 --> 00:24:29,256
[SPEAKER_19]: In that coalition, would they support Tony Blair as Prime Minister?

341
00:24:29,376 --> 00:24:30,718
[SPEAKER_19]: But it's answered by the first one.

342
00:24:30,738 --> 00:24:31,299
[SPEAKER_19]: It is, yes.

343
00:24:31,319 --> 00:24:32,961
[SPEAKER_30]: Yeah, all right, well, let me put a supplementary.

344
00:24:32,981 --> 00:24:33,242
[SPEAKER_30]: All right.

345
00:24:33,342 --> 00:24:34,043
[SPEAKER_30]: You don't go into...

346
00:24:34,063 --> 00:24:34,604
[SPEAKER_19]: I know you love this.

347
00:24:34,724 --> 00:24:35,385
[SPEAKER_30]: You don't go...

348
00:24:35,405 --> 00:24:35,925
[SPEAKER_15]: I love this issue.

349
00:24:35,945 --> 00:24:37,007
[SPEAKER_30]: You don't go into a coalition.

350
00:24:37,027 --> 00:24:37,508
[SPEAKER_15]: Correct.

351
00:24:37,528 --> 00:24:39,330
[SPEAKER_15]: Would you support Tony Blair?

352
00:24:39,310 --> 00:24:41,272
[SPEAKER_15]: No, I mean, we wouldn't support Tony Blair.

353
00:24:41,392 --> 00:24:46,158
[SPEAKER_15]: If you have a Parliament where there's no overall majority next time, a government's got to be formed.

354
00:24:46,598 --> 00:24:51,023
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, let's not speculate which party's the biggest single party but without a majority.

355
00:24:51,424 --> 00:25:04,338
[SPEAKER_15]: But that party, which has the first opportunity to form a government, is going to have to conduct itself in Parliament by taking account of opposition parties' viewpoints, also dissenting voices in its own party.

356
00:25:04,719 --> 00:25:07,782
[SPEAKER_15]: Now, I think that's a much healthier way to proceed.

357
00:25:07,762 --> 00:25:29,881
[SPEAKER_15]: than what we've had over the last four years in particular, which is a government with a big majority riding roughshod, not just over opposition opinions, but over the substantial opinions of its own members of Parliament, which is why you get student fees when they said they wouldn't, which is why you get a war in Iraq, which is why they say they're not putting up tax, and then they turn around and increase national insurance.

358
00:25:30,201 --> 00:25:34,785
[SPEAKER_15]: No wonder, heavens almighty, people are so cynical about politics in this country.

359
00:25:36,567 --> 00:25:37,768
[SPEAKER_15]: If politicians had to listen a bit more, it would be better.

360
00:25:37,748 --> 00:25:41,937
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes.

361
00:25:42,625 --> 00:25:45,248
[SPEAKER_20]: So if they had a different leader, would the answer still be no?

362
00:25:45,328 --> 00:26:04,207
[SPEAKER_15]: The answer would still be no, because the six years I've been leader of the Liberal Democrats, I'm, the last time I counted, on my third leader of the Conservative Party, and I don't base my political activity by who happens to be leader of the Tory Party, and I'm certainly not going to base my future activity by who may or may not be leader of the Labour Party.

363
00:26:04,527 --> 00:26:09,072
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm confident about myself and about the Liberal Democrats, and the other two can look after themselves.

364
00:26:09,052 --> 00:26:10,788
[SPEAKER_30]: Who would you prefer to have as Prime Minister?

365
00:26:11,070 --> 00:26:11,756
[SPEAKER_15]: Charles Kennedy.

366
00:26:11,938 --> 00:26:13,088
[SPEAKER_30]: Apart from Charles Kennedy.

367
00:26:20,729 --> 00:26:35,257
[SPEAKER_30]: I looked at your map where you said if everybody who was thinking of voting Liberal Democrat voted, this is what the picture of the country would look like.

368
00:26:35,518 --> 00:26:40,307
[SPEAKER_30]: It was 100 short of a majority, so even you don't believe you're going to form the next government, you don't believe you're going to be Prime

369
00:26:40,287 --> 00:26:42,070
[SPEAKER_30]: You don't believe you're going to be the biggest party?

370
00:26:42,150 --> 00:26:53,548
[SPEAKER_15]: What we absolutely acknowledge is that the one thing you've got in British politics is no party, Labour, Conservative or Liberal Democrat, under whatever voting system, can say we speak for the majority.

371
00:26:53,748 --> 00:26:54,429
[SPEAKER_15]: None of us do.

372
00:26:54,750 --> 00:26:56,473
[SPEAKER_15]: We are competing minorities.

373
00:26:56,773 --> 00:27:01,921
[SPEAKER_15]: And we've got a very perverse voting system, which I think is going to throw up a very unpredictable election result.

374
00:27:01,941 --> 00:27:05,106
[SPEAKER_15]: So who emerges as the biggest is anybody's guess right now.

375
00:27:05,126 --> 00:27:06,328
[SPEAKER_15]: OK, you, sir.

376
00:27:06,308 --> 00:27:13,180
[SPEAKER_09]: If Gordon Brown takes over midterm, would you consider a coalition party?

377
00:27:13,660 --> 00:27:22,275
[SPEAKER_15]: No, because I don't think that if you are in the serious business of politics, and whether you agree with me or not in this room or watching this programme,

378
00:27:22,255 --> 00:27:27,730
[SPEAKER_15]: What you do want from your politicians, I think, is a consistency of principle and values.

379
00:27:28,171 --> 00:27:36,934
[SPEAKER_15]: And you can't, by definition in my view, be consistent and principled about your values and your approach if you're willing to shuffle around with them.

380
00:27:36,954 --> 00:27:37,716
[SPEAKER_15]: What do you do in Scotland?

381
00:27:37,696 --> 00:27:52,738
[SPEAKER_15]: In Scotland, the difference is you have a voting system which recognises that in Scotland... Why not jump out of the voting system in Westminster and start doing exactly what you do in Scotland, negotiating, make conditions, do deals, why not?

382
00:27:52,878 --> 00:27:56,143
[SPEAKER_30]: What purpose is the Liberal Democrat Party if you don't do that?

383
00:27:56,123 --> 00:27:57,225
[SPEAKER_15]: if you're in a hung Parliament?

384
00:27:57,305 --> 00:27:59,869
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I'll try and answer if you stop asking so many questions.

385
00:28:01,130 --> 00:28:09,904
[SPEAKER_15]: The issue is this in Scotland, you have a voting system which does reflect the minority nature of each of the parties and that means there's an obligation on the parties after an election to cooperate.

386
00:28:10,224 --> 00:28:16,073
[SPEAKER_15]: There is no such obligation at Westminster because we've got a thoroughly perverse, unjust voting system.

387
00:28:16,233 --> 00:28:17,575
[SPEAKER_15]: One more brief point from you.

388
00:28:17,555 --> 00:28:19,658
[SPEAKER_41]: I agree with you about the electoral system.

389
00:28:19,678 --> 00:28:25,167
[SPEAKER_41]: So if you did get into government, would you work to bring a proportional representation system in for Britain?

390
00:28:25,308 --> 00:28:26,209
[SPEAKER_15]: You bet I would.

391
00:28:26,570 --> 00:28:27,992
[SPEAKER_15]: And you bet I would.

392
00:28:28,333 --> 00:28:35,344
[SPEAKER_15]: Not just because if we were in a position to do that on our own, we'd have won under the existing system.

393
00:28:35,324 --> 00:28:37,769
[SPEAKER_15]: but that doesn't justify the existing system.

394
00:28:37,789 --> 00:28:38,871
[SPEAKER_15]: So you would do a deal on that?

395
00:28:39,071 --> 00:28:39,312
[SPEAKER_15]: No.

396
00:28:39,953 --> 00:28:41,096
[SPEAKER_15]: We would put forward...

397
00:28:41,116 --> 00:28:43,681
[SPEAKER_15]: I hope that all politicians would recognise something.

398
00:28:43,961 --> 00:28:54,362
[SPEAKER_15]: There's one thing that's a bit more important than the self-interest of our parties, and it is the equal value, whatever constituency, whatever political persuasion they may be,

399
00:28:54,342 --> 00:28:57,266
[SPEAKER_15]: of voters where their vote is concerned.

400
00:28:57,286 --> 00:29:01,312
[SPEAKER_15]: At the moment, too many people's votes are corrupted by having to vote tactically.

401
00:29:01,672 --> 00:29:12,126
[SPEAKER_15]: I want people at this election, and I believe they are, going to go out there and vote for values and principles and a bit of hope in our country.

402
00:29:12,146 --> 00:29:13,028
[SPEAKER_40]: Charles Kennedy, thank you very much indeed.

403
00:29:13,048 --> 00:29:13,248
[SPEAKER_40]: Thank you.

404
00:29:13,268 --> 00:29:13,448
[SPEAKER_40]: Pleasure.

405
00:29:13,468 --> 00:29:13,869
[SPEAKER_40]: Thank you very much.

406
00:29:13,889 --> 00:29:14,089
[SPEAKER_40]: Thank you.

407
00:29:24,802 --> 00:29:26,044
[SPEAKER_30]: All right.

408
00:29:26,064 --> 00:29:26,905
[SPEAKER_30]: All right.

409
00:29:27,045 --> 00:29:33,613
[SPEAKER_30]: Now we hear from the man who took over the leadership of the Conservative Party from Iain Duncan Smith just 18 months ago, Michael Howard.

410
00:29:43,866 --> 00:29:46,570
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr Howard, your first question comes from Gary Horsman, please.

411
00:29:47,931 --> 00:29:52,277
[SPEAKER_00]: If your family were still in the country of their origin, would you let them into the UK?

412
00:29:59,665 --> 00:30:03,355
[SPEAKER_25]: I would do what I do on every question that faces me.

413
00:30:04,317 --> 00:30:05,561
[SPEAKER_25]: I would do what's best for Britain.

414
00:30:06,543 --> 00:30:14,805
[SPEAKER_25]: Now what I think is best for Britain is that we have a system of immigration control which works, which is fair.

415
00:30:15,342 --> 00:30:16,845
[SPEAKER_25]: and which has limits on it.

416
00:30:17,827 --> 00:30:19,771
[SPEAKER_25]: I think that you need those limits.

417
00:30:20,392 --> 00:30:27,808
[SPEAKER_25]: Immigration has increased three times since Mr Blair came to office without anybody being consulted or asked about it.

418
00:30:28,349 --> 00:30:32,016
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, my father came to this country as an economic migrant.

419
00:30:32,036 --> 00:30:33,840
[SPEAKER_25]: He came to do a job.

420
00:30:33,820 --> 00:30:40,308
[SPEAKER_25]: and we would make provision within our limits for people whose skills were needed in this country who come to do jobs.

421
00:30:40,388 --> 00:30:46,956
[SPEAKER_25]: And we'd do that after consulting with the employers' organisations to make sure that we get people with the necessary skills.

422
00:30:47,316 --> 00:30:48,678
[SPEAKER_25]: That's the right thing for Britain.

423
00:30:49,059 --> 00:30:49,719
[SPEAKER_25]: That's what I would do.

424
00:30:49,960 --> 00:30:53,884
[SPEAKER_30]: And it would depend on whether they'd reach the limit that you wanted, whether they got in or not?

425
00:30:54,045 --> 00:30:54,525
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes, it would.

426
00:30:54,906 --> 00:30:55,667
[SPEAKER_30]: So they might not get in?

427
00:30:55,847 --> 00:30:56,407
[SPEAKER_30]: That's possible.

428
00:30:56,528 --> 00:30:57,749
[SPEAKER_30]: Gary Horstman, does that answer your question?

429
00:30:57,769 --> 00:30:58,670
[SPEAKER_30]: We've got to do what's right for Britain.

430
00:30:58,690 --> 00:31:00,132
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr Horstman, does that answer your question?

431
00:31:00,213 --> 00:31:06,242
[SPEAKER_00]: I think the question wasn't necessarily designed to have an answer that I had an opinion about, it's really just opening up the debate.

432
00:31:06,262 --> 00:31:09,888
[SPEAKER_00]: The reason why I asked the question in the first place is because I think there's a lot of posturing about it.

433
00:31:09,908 --> 00:31:20,545
[SPEAKER_00]: It was very interesting the question time a few weeks ago when you added an independent journalist on here, who gave a whole different set of statistics and opinions about what's going on with the immigration debate.

434
00:31:20,565 --> 00:31:24,190
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't think we really get that kind of real debate about immigration going on.

435
00:31:24,210 --> 00:31:25,593
[SPEAKER_24]: I think there's a lot of posturing going on.

436
00:31:25,613 --> 00:31:27,115
[SPEAKER_30]: OK, the man there, can I ask a question?

437
00:31:27,095 --> 00:31:32,151
[SPEAKER_24]: What you're really saying is that the only way in which you would let people into this country is on whether they're good for this country.

438
00:31:32,192 --> 00:31:34,599
[SPEAKER_24]: What about those people who'd be murdered if they went back home?

439
00:31:34,860 --> 00:31:36,987
[SPEAKER_24]: The people who'd be tortured if they went back?

440
00:31:40,814 --> 00:31:48,863
[SPEAKER_24]: that the people of Scotland say, and I've read the Scotsman three times on this subject, that they'd like some of those immigrants up there and this government isn't sending them up there.

441
00:31:48,883 --> 00:31:50,665
[SPEAKER_24]: You aren't even talking about filling that gap.

442
00:31:51,226 --> 00:31:55,931
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, I was in Scotland yesterday actually talking about precisely that, but let me answer your question because it's not the case.

443
00:31:55,951 --> 00:31:56,712
[SPEAKER_25]: What did you say to them?

444
00:31:56,732 --> 00:31:57,633
[SPEAKER_25]: That I would...

445
00:31:57,813 --> 00:31:58,233
[SPEAKER_25]: I said...

446
00:31:58,293 --> 00:31:58,994
[SPEAKER_25]: In Scotland, that is.

447
00:31:59,014 --> 00:32:01,357
[SPEAKER_25]: Right, I said I'd deal with Scotland, but I must deal with the other point as well.

448
00:32:01,377 --> 00:32:03,379
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, you just said you were up in Scotland and you were talking to them.

449
00:32:03,359 --> 00:32:04,101
[SPEAKER_25]: Sure, I was.

450
00:32:04,441 --> 00:32:16,667
[SPEAKER_25]: And what I said was that when, first of all, when we have our point system to decide who comes into the country with the skills that we need, we would give extra points for people who want to go to Scotland if their skills are needed in Scotland.

451
00:32:16,928 --> 00:32:22,600
[SPEAKER_25]: The problem Scotland faces is that a lot of their young people are leaving Scotland.

452
00:32:22,580 --> 00:32:24,746
[SPEAKER_25]: with unlimited immigration, uncontrolled immigration.

453
00:32:24,806 --> 00:32:32,767
[SPEAKER_25]: The reason they are leaving Scotland is because the Scottish economy is doing much less well than the economy of the rest of the country, the rest of the United Kingdom.

454
00:32:33,208 --> 00:32:36,477
[SPEAKER_25]: David, please let me answer the first question the gentleman posed because it is a very important one.

455
00:32:36,818 --> 00:32:38,783
[SPEAKER_25]: We have never said

456
00:32:38,763 --> 00:32:42,952
[SPEAKER_25]: that the only people we'd let in would be people with the skills that are needed in this country.

457
00:32:42,972 --> 00:32:43,893
[SPEAKER_25]: That's not the policy.

458
00:32:44,314 --> 00:32:46,379
[SPEAKER_25]: There would be three groups of people we'd let in.

459
00:32:46,739 --> 00:32:55,978
[SPEAKER_25]: The first are those people whose skills we need, the second are those people who want to come into the country for family reunion, and the third are refugees, genuine refugees,

460
00:32:55,958 --> 00:32:59,601
[SPEAKER_25]: We'd have more genuine refugees come into the country than come in now.

461
00:32:59,902 --> 00:33:08,830
[SPEAKER_25]: The problem now is that we have a very unfair, inhumane system which rewards those people who pay the people smugglers who traffic people across the world.

462
00:33:09,090 --> 00:33:10,512
[SPEAKER_25]: And I want to put an end to that.

463
00:33:17,058 --> 00:33:23,704
[SPEAKER_38]: Do you think if your quota had been reached it would be good for Britain if valuable doctors and nurses were not allowed into the country?

464
00:33:23,954 --> 00:33:33,561
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, I believe that our limit for those with the skills that we need would include proper provision for doctors and nurses who we need to come into the country.

465
00:33:33,581 --> 00:33:35,065
[SPEAKER_25]: But let me say something else about that.

466
00:33:35,446 --> 00:33:36,770
[SPEAKER_25]: We have a problem at the moment.

467
00:33:37,211 --> 00:33:38,976
[SPEAKER_25]: We have a problem because

468
00:33:38,956 --> 00:33:46,987
[SPEAKER_25]: Vast numbers of nurses working in the health service at the moment are leaving because they're fed up with the system we have at the moment.

469
00:33:47,368 --> 00:33:55,299
[SPEAKER_25]: And that's why we have to bring in nurses from abroad, often from countries which need those nurses, to stay there and nurse people in those countries.

470
00:33:55,679 --> 00:34:06,375
[SPEAKER_25]: I'd far rather we kept nurses in our health service by having a system that helps them rather than hinders them, so they didn't leave the health service in the considerable numbers that they're doing today.

471
00:34:06,695 --> 00:34:07,716
[SPEAKER_25]: All right.

472
00:34:07,736 --> 00:34:08,878
[SPEAKER_25]: And the woman at the very back there.

473
00:34:08,858 --> 00:34:13,671
[SPEAKER_16]: If you're talking about limits on immigration, would you pull out of the Geneva Convention?

474
00:34:13,870 --> 00:34:17,976
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, because I think it's out of date, and indeed Mr Blair agrees with me on that.

475
00:34:18,056 --> 00:34:19,057
[SPEAKER_25]: He said it's out of date.

476
00:34:19,438 --> 00:34:21,421
[SPEAKER_25]: It was entered into more than 50 years ago.

477
00:34:21,501 --> 00:34:30,694
[SPEAKER_25]: It doesn't reflect the needs of today's world, and the difference between me and Mr Blair is that he talks about it, but I would actually do it.

478
00:34:30,895 --> 00:34:31,856
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it's out of date.

479
00:34:32,056 --> 00:34:35,101
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't think it reflects the modern world, and yes, we would pull out of it.

480
00:34:35,501 --> 00:34:37,744
[SPEAKER_25]: Gary Horsman, do you want to come back in on this?

481
00:34:37,865 --> 00:34:38,686
[SPEAKER_25]: Oh, you want to come back on it?

482
00:34:38,706 --> 00:34:39,507
[SPEAKER_16]: Sorry, yes, go on.

483
00:34:39,487 --> 00:34:44,275
[SPEAKER_16]: So, would you want it replaced with something else, or do you think it's just up to individual states?

484
00:34:44,295 --> 00:34:48,622
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, I think if we could get a sensible international agreement, that would be a very good thing.

485
00:34:48,982 --> 00:35:06,490
[SPEAKER_25]: I tried... You know, when I was Home Secretary, I tried to get international agreement at the United Nations that you shouldn't allow someone who is a terrorist to go through the whole panoply of appeals and procedures that you have to allow them to go through today.

486
00:35:06,740 --> 00:35:09,273
[SPEAKER_25]: And I failed to get agreement even on that.

487
00:35:09,755 --> 00:35:12,248
[SPEAKER_25]: So I'd like to get a new international agreement.

488
00:35:12,268 --> 00:35:14,961
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not terribly optimistic that it would be easy to get.

489
00:35:15,481 --> 00:35:19,467
[SPEAKER_21]: how can you actually justify pulling out of the 1951 Refugee Convention?

490
00:35:19,507 --> 00:35:32,205
[SPEAKER_21]: I can understand saying that you want to amend it to perhaps consider things like internally displaced people, but to actually say you want to pull out of the Refugee Convention, which more than 140 states signed up to it, not a single country has actually pulled out of the Refugee Convention.

491
00:35:32,565 --> 00:35:35,089
[SPEAKER_21]: You want to make Britain be the first country to pull out of it.

492
00:35:35,129 --> 00:35:44,442
[SPEAKER_21]: And secondly, I mean, your policies just sound to be very anti-human rights, just like the same way you want to scrap the Human Rights Act as well, for no good reason at all.

493
00:35:44,590 --> 00:35:47,495
[SPEAKER_25]: Let me deal with both those questions.

494
00:35:48,136 --> 00:35:51,201
[SPEAKER_25]: First of all, yes, I think it's out of date and that's why I want to pull out of it.

495
00:35:51,261 --> 00:35:56,890
[SPEAKER_25]: But I emphasise we would take genuine refugees, more genuine refugees than come into this country today.

496
00:35:57,050 --> 00:35:58,332
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we have a duty to do that.

497
00:35:58,673 --> 00:36:04,102
[SPEAKER_25]: I want this country to continue to give sanctuary, but not to the people who pay the people traffickers.

498
00:36:04,542 --> 00:36:11,053
[SPEAKER_25]: I want to give sanctuary to the mothers and the children who can't afford to pay the people smugglers,

499
00:36:11,033 --> 00:36:15,119
[SPEAKER_25]: who aren't strong enough to be transported in the backs of lorries halfway across the world.

500
00:36:15,399 --> 00:36:16,220
[SPEAKER_25]: That's what I want to do.

501
00:36:16,260 --> 00:36:20,005
[SPEAKER_25]: I want a much fairer and more humane system than we have today.

502
00:36:20,045 --> 00:36:24,611
[SPEAKER_25]: OK, let's have a question from Lucy Elliott.

503
00:36:24,631 --> 00:36:26,774
[SPEAKER_30]: Lucy Elliott, please.

504
00:36:27,035 --> 00:36:37,209
[SPEAKER_39]: Calling people liars and raising potentially damaging issues over immigration, do you worry about the effect your negative campaign is having on our society?

505
00:36:38,110 --> 00:36:39,792
[SPEAKER_25]: Lucy, we have put forward...

506
00:36:43,366 --> 00:36:49,539
[SPEAKER_25]: We've put forward from the beginning of this campaign the things we want to do for our country.

507
00:36:50,120 --> 00:36:55,852
[SPEAKER_25]: Our five commitments are cleaner hospitals, school discipline, more police, controlled immigration, lower taxes.

508
00:36:55,872 --> 00:37:00,582
[SPEAKER_25]: Let me tell you a little bit about the importance of school discipline.

509
00:37:00,562 --> 00:37:02,044
[SPEAKER_25]: School discipline is crucial.

510
00:37:02,064 --> 00:37:03,866
[SPEAKER_25]: I went to a terrific school this afternoon.

511
00:37:04,107 --> 00:37:05,429
[SPEAKER_25]: It was a joy to behold.

512
00:37:05,709 --> 00:37:08,593
[SPEAKER_25]: And there are some many tremendous schools in our country.

513
00:37:08,713 --> 00:37:21,570
[SPEAKER_25]: But there are many where children just are having their education wrecked because of the activities of one or two disruptive children in the class who spoil the opportunity for others to learn.

514
00:37:21,610 --> 00:37:23,112
[SPEAKER_25]: So we have to do something about that.

515
00:37:23,152 --> 00:37:25,676
[SPEAKER_25]: And what we do is give headteachers the right to exclude.

516
00:37:25,716 --> 00:37:28,780
[SPEAKER_25]: So we've been putting forward our plans.

517
00:37:28,760 --> 00:37:30,505
[SPEAKER_25]: It's a choice at this election.

518
00:37:31,026 --> 00:37:33,793
[SPEAKER_25]: It's a choice between parties with different programmes.

519
00:37:34,375 --> 00:37:44,862
[SPEAKER_25]: And one of the things that people have to take into account when they decide is not only the programmes that the parties are putting forward, but whether those parties are likely to deliver on their promises.

520
00:37:44,842 --> 00:37:58,999
[SPEAKER_25]: and if you have a situation in which, as is the case with Mr Blair, that before 1997, he said there'd be no need to increase taxes, and he did immediately afterwards, and he did the same thing before the last election, and he promised, he said he was opposed to...

521
00:37:59,019 --> 00:38:00,701
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not sure you're answering Lucy Allitt's point.

522
00:38:00,961 --> 00:38:01,582
[SPEAKER_25]: I think I am, Liz.

523
00:38:01,602 --> 00:38:06,748
[SPEAKER_30]: Because you're talking about Mr Blair, and we're here... We're here... We're here...

524
00:38:07,724 --> 00:38:16,353
[SPEAKER_30]: We're here to listen to you talk about your policies, and I want to go back to Lucy Elliott and just ask you what it was you were thinking of, and whether Mr Howard is answering your point.

525
00:38:16,373 --> 00:38:31,127
[SPEAKER_39]: Yeah, I think that the campaign from the Tories seems to be terribly negative, and I keep hearing about liars, and I've had children who are now talking about Tony Blair being a liar, which I don't think is healthy.

526
00:38:31,167 --> 00:38:32,329
[SPEAKER_39]: You're talking about schools.

527
00:38:32,629 --> 00:38:36,853
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't want children to think that, as adults, we can go around accusing people

528
00:38:36,833 --> 00:38:38,034
[SPEAKER_39]: of being liars.

529
00:38:38,334 --> 00:38:40,377
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, let's see.

530
00:38:42,158 --> 00:38:45,782
[SPEAKER_25]: How many people in this audience think that Mr Blair told the truth about the war?

531
00:38:46,743 --> 00:38:47,323
[SPEAKER_25]: Put up your hands.

532
00:38:47,784 --> 00:38:50,547
[SPEAKER_25]: There aren't very many, so it doesn't look as though I'm alone.

533
00:38:50,567 --> 00:38:55,552
[SPEAKER_25]: And the important thing is that if you are to make an assessment...

534
00:38:55,572 --> 00:38:59,395
[SPEAKER_30]: The word liar was what it was about, Mr Howard, not about whether people thought people were telling the truth.

535
00:38:59,435 --> 00:39:02,318
[SPEAKER_30]: It's the use of the word liar, I think, isn't it, that you're objecting to.

536
00:39:02,378 --> 00:39:02,999
[SPEAKER_30]: That's the objection.

537
00:39:03,019 --> 00:39:05,001
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, I'm afraid I tell it like it is.

538
00:39:04,981 --> 00:39:10,688
[SPEAKER_25]: And I tell it as I see it, I'm afraid.

539
00:39:10,938 --> 00:39:12,680
[SPEAKER_25]: What you see is what you get, I'm afraid.

540
00:39:13,041 --> 00:39:14,643
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm going to be perfectly honest and straight.

541
00:39:14,743 --> 00:39:15,544
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm very direct.

542
00:39:16,005 --> 00:39:31,364
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think that it's important that people are able to take into account in deciding whether someone's going to keep their promises and deliver on their programs the extent to which they've done so in the past or the extent to which they've misled people in the past.

543
00:39:31,384 --> 00:39:33,147
[SPEAKER_30]: Is George W. Bush a liar as well as Tony Blair?

544
00:39:33,167 --> 00:39:36,551
[SPEAKER_25]: No, he justified the war on Iraq on an entirely different basis.

545
00:39:36,631 --> 00:39:37,452
[SPEAKER_27]: Michael Howard.

546
00:39:37,432 --> 00:39:39,479
[SPEAKER_27]: I know you hate me because I'm an asylum seeker, yeah?

547
00:39:39,499 --> 00:39:39,920
[SPEAKER_27]: No, I don't.

548
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:40,823
[SPEAKER_27]: No, of course you do.

549
00:39:40,883 --> 00:39:41,124
[SPEAKER_27]: No.

550
00:39:41,344 --> 00:39:44,535
[SPEAKER_27]: And the language you use towards asylum seekers are insane, I tell you.

551
00:39:44,795 --> 00:39:46,260
[SPEAKER_27]: You don't know what it feels like, yeah?

552
00:39:47,168 --> 00:39:49,652
[SPEAKER_27]: What you're saying towards asylum seekers, you're treating them as dirt.

553
00:39:50,533 --> 00:39:52,717
[SPEAKER_27]: Racism is not even a word for it.

554
00:39:52,837 --> 00:39:55,001
[SPEAKER_27]: You see them as dirt, as filthy, like Hitler.

555
00:39:55,241 --> 00:39:59,828
[SPEAKER_27]: You should see you and your parents 60 years ago, all right, before you came into this country, and I'll tell you that.

556
00:40:00,069 --> 00:40:02,112
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, I'm afraid I completely disagree with you.

557
00:40:02,533 --> 00:40:04,316
[SPEAKER_25]: I want...

558
00:40:04,336 --> 00:40:04,676
[SPEAKER_25]: I want...

559
00:40:04,696 --> 00:40:07,741
[SPEAKER_25]: I don't know how you came to the country or where you come from.

560
00:40:07,861 --> 00:40:08,803
[SPEAKER_25]: You don't know what it feels like.

561
00:40:08,823 --> 00:40:14,492
[SPEAKER_27]: But I want to give... You can't talk about a human being like that, because you're an asylum seeker yourself, and you're your parents, do you know what I mean?

562
00:40:14,472 --> 00:40:16,537
[SPEAKER_25]: No, that's not actually true.

563
00:40:16,557 --> 00:40:20,105
[SPEAKER_25]: But I want more genuine refugees in this country than come today.

564
00:40:20,646 --> 00:40:24,956
[SPEAKER_27]: I tell you how we do it.

565
00:40:25,377 --> 00:40:27,282
[SPEAKER_25]: We would take people from the United Nations.

566
00:40:27,342 --> 00:40:28,926
[SPEAKER_25]: There are people all over the world.

567
00:40:30,249 --> 00:40:32,093
[SPEAKER_25]: Mothers and children.

568
00:40:32,073 --> 00:40:33,977
[SPEAKER_25]: who desperately need sanctuary.

569
00:40:34,237 --> 00:40:41,412
[SPEAKER_25]: They are the people we should be giving sanctuary to, not people, I don't know how you came here, I don't know your circumstances, but the truth is...

570
00:40:41,452 --> 00:40:45,300
[SPEAKER_27]: I think you have been very evil.

571
00:40:45,320 --> 00:40:47,725
[SPEAKER_27]: I am afraid the truth is...

572
00:40:47,765 --> 00:40:52,495
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't understand how the British government allows people for you to be in a government.

573
00:40:52,475 --> 00:40:54,780
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm afraid the truth is... No, I want to go on to somebody else.

574
00:40:54,921 --> 00:40:56,324
[SPEAKER_30]: The man at the back there in the white shirt.

575
00:40:56,424 --> 00:40:56,905
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you.

576
00:40:56,945 --> 00:41:01,436
[SPEAKER_31]: Mr Howard, is the Labour government putting pupils and students under too much pressure these days?

577
00:41:01,596 --> 00:41:06,789
[SPEAKER_31]: In the last at least seven years, I must have taken at least 60, 70 written exams.

578
00:41:07,250 --> 00:41:08,011
[SPEAKER_31]: That is too much.

579
00:41:10,156 --> 00:41:10,838
[SPEAKER_28]: Right.

580
00:41:11,206 --> 00:41:15,052
[SPEAKER_30]: It's an off-the-wall question, but if you'd like to answer it...

581
00:41:15,072 --> 00:41:16,033
[SPEAKER_30]: It's a very interesting one.

582
00:41:16,053 --> 00:41:19,398
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes, yes, but don't go on too long about it, if you don't mind, because we've got a long agenda here tonight.

583
00:41:19,418 --> 00:41:23,264
[SPEAKER_25]: Hang on, it's a very important one, because there's nothing more important than education.

584
00:41:23,825 --> 00:41:26,029
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think the answer to your question is almost certainly yes.

585
00:41:26,329 --> 00:41:35,543
[SPEAKER_25]: What we've said we would do is to set up a committee under Chris Woodhead to look at the curriculum, to see if the national curriculum can be slimmed down,

586
00:41:35,523 --> 00:41:40,409
[SPEAKER_25]: to look again at the kind of exams which people sit and the tests which they sit.

587
00:41:40,930 --> 00:41:53,165
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we've got to keep the exams, but we've got to make the exams more useful than they are today, more useful to the people who sit the exams and more useful to the employers who need to be guided by them too often.

588
00:41:53,405 --> 00:41:54,326
[SPEAKER_25]: They're a smokescreen.

589
00:41:54,506 --> 00:41:56,088
[SPEAKER_25]: Let's just go back to where we were.

590
00:41:56,128 --> 00:41:58,131
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, just reverting back to the liar.

591
00:41:58,591 --> 00:42:00,874
[SPEAKER_31]: In the polls at the moment, you're a bit behind Labour.

592
00:42:00,914 --> 00:42:04,078
[SPEAKER_31]: How does it feel to be less trusted than someone you've called a liar?

593
00:42:10,589 --> 00:42:16,878
[SPEAKER_25]: Different polls say different things about that, and as I often say, there's only one poll that matters, and it's the one that's going to take place a week today.

594
00:42:16,998 --> 00:42:17,298
[SPEAKER_25]: All right.

595
00:42:17,318 --> 00:42:17,779
[SPEAKER_25]: Anu, sir.

596
00:42:18,460 --> 00:42:21,364
[SPEAKER_10]: I think Michael Howard's absolutely right to call Tony Blair a liar.

597
00:42:21,705 --> 00:42:22,205
[SPEAKER_10]: He's had...

598
00:42:22,225 --> 00:42:27,593
[SPEAKER_10]: He's got...

599
00:42:27,713 --> 00:42:30,717
[SPEAKER_10]: He's got eight years of form of lying to the British people.

600
00:42:30,777 --> 00:42:33,982
[SPEAKER_10]: There's soldiers from my town who are dead because of his lies.

601
00:42:34,382 --> 00:42:39,229
[SPEAKER_10]: The only people in this country who believe Tony Blair are Mrs Blair and Alastair Campbell.

602
00:42:40,255 --> 00:42:42,641
[SPEAKER_30]: Let's move on.

603
00:42:42,681 --> 00:42:44,887
[SPEAKER_30]: A question from Ahmad Khwaja, please.

604
00:42:45,087 --> 00:42:45,689
[SPEAKER_30]: Ahmad Khwaja.

605
00:42:46,210 --> 00:42:46,611
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

606
00:42:47,193 --> 00:42:56,577
[SPEAKER_11]: Mr. Howard, would you and the Conservative Party supported the Iraq war had you known then what you know now?

607
00:42:57,367 --> 00:43:11,957
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, the answer I'm about to give is probably one, Ahmed, that you won't agree with, and that a lot of other people won't agree with, but I have to say it as I see it, and though I have total respect for the views of those who disagree with me, my answer is this.

608
00:43:12,157 --> 00:43:14,903
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, I would have supported the war,

609
00:43:14,883 --> 00:43:19,691
[SPEAKER_25]: because I think it was the right thing to do.

610
00:43:20,532 --> 00:43:23,677
[SPEAKER_25]: Saddam Hussein had been in breach of many United Nations resolutions.

611
00:43:23,778 --> 00:43:28,746
[SPEAKER_25]: I think he was a threat to the peace of the region and a threat to the wider peace in the world.

612
00:43:29,246 --> 00:43:35,136
[SPEAKER_25]: But I think that it was possible to go to war and to tell the truth.

613
00:43:35,183 --> 00:43:36,605
[SPEAKER_25]: And I don't think Mr Blair did that.

614
00:43:37,126 --> 00:43:40,331
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think it was possible to go to war and have a plan.

615
00:43:40,932 --> 00:43:47,884
[SPEAKER_25]: And we were saying at the time, where is your plan for what happens after Saddam Hussein has been deposed?

616
00:43:48,324 --> 00:43:52,551
[SPEAKER_25]: And if we'd had a plan, I think we could have avoided many of the mistakes that were made.

617
00:43:52,611 --> 00:43:59,723
[SPEAKER_25]: For example, the disbandment of the Iraqi army and the Iraqi police, which should have been kept in place under a different command.

618
00:43:59,703 --> 00:44:06,197
[SPEAKER_25]: And if that had been done, we could probably have avoided many of the difficulties which we still face today.

619
00:44:06,217 --> 00:44:13,351
[SPEAKER_30]: But Mr Howard, the question was, if you knew now what you didn't know then, would you have gone to war?

620
00:44:13,371 --> 00:44:15,937
[SPEAKER_30]: What you know now is there were no weapons of mass destruction.

621
00:44:15,957 --> 00:44:20,867
[SPEAKER_30]: Are you saying you would have still gone to war against Iraq if you'd known there were no WMD in Iraq?

622
00:44:20,847 --> 00:44:22,369
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, that's exactly what I'm saying.

623
00:44:22,389 --> 00:44:22,890
[SPEAKER_25]: On what grounds?

624
00:44:22,910 --> 00:44:29,400
[SPEAKER_25]: On the grounds that I've just given, that Saddam Hussein was a threat to the peace of the region, was a threat to wider peace.

625
00:44:29,801 --> 00:44:33,186
[SPEAKER_25]: He had tried to get weapons of mass destruction in the past and used them.

626
00:44:33,447 --> 00:44:38,194
[SPEAKER_25]: He would have tried again, and he was in breach of several United Nations Security Council resolutions.

627
00:44:38,254 --> 00:44:42,281
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, that's not a view that will meet with universal approval or agreement, but it's as I see it.

628
00:44:42,301 --> 00:44:44,965
[SPEAKER_25]: Would it meet with the Attorney General's approval, do you think?

629
00:44:44,945 --> 00:44:46,748
[SPEAKER_25]: That you'll have to ask the Attorney General.

630
00:44:46,768 --> 00:44:47,630
[SPEAKER_25]: No, but you think.

631
00:44:47,650 --> 00:44:49,653
[SPEAKER_25]: You're a lawyer, you've been talking about this all day.

632
00:44:49,673 --> 00:44:54,261
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, and the Attorney General recognises that there's... No WMD and you can still go to war against Saddam.

633
00:44:54,281 --> 00:44:54,962
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes, I think so.

634
00:44:54,982 --> 00:44:58,709
[SPEAKER_25]: The Attorney General recognises that there's more than one view and that's the view I take.

635
00:44:59,009 --> 00:45:01,995
[SPEAKER_25]: Isn't that a regime change war rather than anything to do with the United Nations?

636
00:45:02,015 --> 00:45:05,080
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, it's regime change plus because I also...

637
00:45:05,060 --> 00:45:08,586
[SPEAKER_25]: I also mentioned the breach of the United Nations Security Resolutions.

638
00:45:08,606 --> 00:45:10,750
[SPEAKER_25]: You have to take the whole thing into account.

639
00:45:10,830 --> 00:45:12,052
[SPEAKER_25]: Even if he's not a threat?

640
00:45:12,633 --> 00:45:13,635
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, I think he was a threat.

641
00:45:13,655 --> 00:45:14,336
[SPEAKER_25]: You can be a threat.

642
00:45:14,356 --> 00:45:15,418
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, no WMD.

643
00:45:15,518 --> 00:45:16,239
[SPEAKER_30]: But you can still be a threat.

644
00:45:16,259 --> 00:45:17,001
[SPEAKER_30]: I'll go back to the question.

645
00:45:17,161 --> 00:45:22,230
[SPEAKER_11]: But isn't regime change illegal under United Nations regulations?

646
00:45:22,650 --> 00:45:26,998
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, as I say... How many regimes are there in this world which we should change?

647
00:45:27,459 --> 00:45:28,300
[SPEAKER_11]: And we haven't.

648
00:45:35,300 --> 00:45:38,765
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, regime change on its own isn't enough.

649
00:45:38,825 --> 00:45:40,468
[SPEAKER_25]: You have to have other things as well.

650
00:45:40,488 --> 00:45:46,297
[SPEAKER_25]: And what you had in the case of Saddam Hussein was the breach of a number of United Nations Security Council resolutions.

651
00:45:46,697 --> 00:45:49,461
[SPEAKER_25]: And you had Security Council Resolution 1441.

652
00:45:49,962 --> 00:45:52,306
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, the interpretation of that is quite controversial.

653
00:45:52,967 --> 00:45:58,074
[SPEAKER_25]: But there is a perfectly respectable view that that did provide the basis for the action that was taken.

654
00:45:58,415 --> 00:45:59,476
[SPEAKER_25]: And that's my view.

655
00:45:59,536 --> 00:46:01,519
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, you're perfectly entitled to disagree with it.

656
00:46:01,960 --> 00:46:02,641
[SPEAKER_25]: But that's my view.

657
00:46:02,962 --> 00:46:03,062
[SPEAKER_25]: OK.

658
00:46:03,082 --> 00:46:04,564
[SPEAKER_25]: The man there with the black tie.

659
00:46:04,544 --> 00:46:10,495
[SPEAKER_12]: So you say you'd go to war with Iraq because he broke UN resolutions, but you'd go there without a UN mandate?

660
00:46:11,657 --> 00:46:12,358
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes.

661
00:46:12,378 --> 00:46:20,112
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, the argument is whether what was contained in Resolution 1441 was a sufficient UN mandate.

662
00:46:20,132 --> 00:46:22,156
[SPEAKER_25]: There was a UN mandate in that resolution.

663
00:46:22,577 --> 00:46:23,899
[SPEAKER_25]: Some people say it wasn't enough.

664
00:46:24,420 --> 00:46:25,622
[SPEAKER_25]: Others say it was enough.

665
00:46:25,682 --> 00:46:26,704
[SPEAKER_25]: That's the argument.

666
00:46:26,802 --> 00:46:28,627
[SPEAKER_30]: Okay, man down here.

667
00:46:28,647 --> 00:46:40,238
[SPEAKER_46]: I think what I find amazing sitting here is that Tony Blair clearly made a mistake going to Iraq and you actually start sitting there saying that you would do the same thing.

668
00:46:41,011 --> 00:46:48,329
[SPEAKER_25]: Look, it would be politically much more convenient for me to say that I think it was a terrible mistake and I wouldn't have done it.

669
00:46:48,770 --> 00:46:51,016
[SPEAKER_25]: But I'm afraid I've got to be straight about it.

670
00:46:51,156 --> 00:46:54,845
[SPEAKER_25]: Even though it is politically inconvenient, I've got to tell you the truth as I see it.

671
00:46:55,126 --> 00:46:57,973
[SPEAKER_25]: And the truth as I see it is that it was the right thing to do.

672
00:46:57,953 --> 00:47:16,755
[SPEAKER_30]: And you would have gone, just to get this absolutely clear, you would have gone, if you'd known all the intelligence that was there and all the things that were discovered subsequently, without any WMD, without any immediate apparent threat, simply on the grounds that he hadn't abided by 1441, by the resolution, regardless of whether there was a real genuine threat to this country

673
00:47:16,735 --> 00:47:18,396
[SPEAKER_25]: or the world at large?

674
00:47:18,517 --> 00:47:19,057
[SPEAKER_25]: No, no, no.

675
00:47:19,237 --> 00:47:20,819
[SPEAKER_25]: I've said it was more than one thing.

676
00:47:20,859 --> 00:47:22,440
[SPEAKER_25]: It was a combination of the fact that...

677
00:47:22,460 --> 00:47:25,223
[SPEAKER_30]: But it can't be regime change, because Goldsmith has said it can't be, under law.

678
00:47:25,543 --> 00:47:28,125
[SPEAKER_25]: Not just regime change, but... Not at all regime change.

679
00:47:28,145 --> 00:47:29,166
[SPEAKER_25]: No, look, David, what I'm saying is...

680
00:47:29,186 --> 00:47:34,871
[SPEAKER_30]: Sorry, what he actually says is regime change cannot be the objective of military action in the thing that was at least released this morning.

681
00:47:34,891 --> 00:47:44,220
[SPEAKER_25]: What I'm saying is that I think he was a threat to the peace of the region, a threat to the wider peace, and he was in breach of United Nations Security Council resolutions.

682
00:47:44,480 --> 00:47:46,742
[SPEAKER_25]: That's my view, and others may disagree.

683
00:47:46,722 --> 00:47:47,223
[SPEAKER_25]: The man there.

684
00:47:48,205 --> 00:47:50,068
[SPEAKER_25]: I'll come to you next.

685
00:47:50,108 --> 00:48:00,808
[SPEAKER_13]: You clearly supported Tony Blair in regime change in Iraq, but would you support it to dispose of another evil dictator such as Robert Mugabe in Zimbabwe?

686
00:48:01,289 --> 00:48:07,600
[SPEAKER_13]: Millions of people die, he might not have weapons of mass destruction, but he's surely just as evil.

687
00:48:13,553 --> 00:48:19,486
[SPEAKER_25]: I would love to be able to get rid of the regime of Robert Mugabe, which I think is one of the most despicable tyrannies on the face of this earth.

688
00:48:19,747 --> 00:48:21,210
[SPEAKER_25]: I would love to be able to do it.

689
00:48:21,671 --> 00:48:30,972
[SPEAKER_25]: But I think it's however awful and despicable that regime is, it's very difficult to argue that it's a threat to the peace outside Zimbabwe.

690
00:48:30,952 --> 00:48:42,866
[SPEAKER_25]: And you can't, as someone else pointed out earlier, I think it was Ahmed suggested earlier, what you can't do is go around the world changing every regime that you think is a bad regime.

691
00:48:42,906 --> 00:48:44,748
[SPEAKER_25]: There are many bad regimes in the world.

692
00:48:45,129 --> 00:48:48,893
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think we should do much more than we're doing now to change them.

693
00:48:48,913 --> 00:48:52,938
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we should be doing much more than we're doing now to try and get rid of Robert Mugabe.

694
00:48:52,958 --> 00:48:53,359
[SPEAKER_25]: But hang on.

695
00:48:53,379 --> 00:48:56,723
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we should have sanctions against Robert Mugabe which are properly enforced.

696
00:48:56,743 --> 00:49:00,267
[SPEAKER_30]: You could go on the basis that it's a humanitarian catastrophe.

697
00:49:00,770 --> 00:49:04,095
[SPEAKER_30]: You could go on the basis of a humanitarian catastrophe, couldn't you?

698
00:49:04,115 --> 00:49:04,936
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, I think that's...

699
00:49:05,036 --> 00:49:06,899
[SPEAKER_30]: Under the UN.

700
00:49:06,919 --> 00:49:12,147
[SPEAKER_30]: I mean, if you want to argue the UN case, if you want to argue the UN case, that's...

701
00:49:12,347 --> 00:49:15,351
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it would be difficult to do that in relation to Zimbabwe.

702
00:49:15,471 --> 00:49:16,293
[SPEAKER_25]: More is the pity.

703
00:49:16,533 --> 00:49:17,655
[SPEAKER_25]: More is the pity.

704
00:49:17,755 --> 00:49:19,177
[SPEAKER_30]: You don't want to go?

705
00:49:19,197 --> 00:49:19,698
[SPEAKER_30]: OK, right.

706
00:49:19,898 --> 00:49:21,400
[SPEAKER_30]: And you, sir, yes, and then we'll move on.

707
00:49:21,761 --> 00:49:27,469
[SPEAKER_32]: If you were in power, would you maintain a nuclear deterrent and would you use it on someone who wanted to change our regime?

708
00:49:28,512 --> 00:49:31,936
[SPEAKER_25]: I would maintain a nuclear deterrent.

709
00:49:32,016 --> 00:49:42,770
[SPEAKER_25]: The whole point of the nuclear deterrent is that it is a deterrent, and it's worked as a deterrent for a very long time, and I think it would continue to work as a deterrent for a long time into the future.

710
00:49:43,090 --> 00:49:52,502
[SPEAKER_25]: But as more countries, unfortunately, seem to be on the point of acquiring weapons of mass destruction, I think we need to be able to deter them from attacking us.

711
00:49:52,762 --> 00:49:53,283
[SPEAKER_25]: All right.

712
00:49:53,303 --> 00:49:55,446
[SPEAKER_30]: Let's move on to a question from Alan Revel, please.

713
00:49:55,586 --> 00:49:56,126
[SPEAKER_30]: Alan Revel?

714
00:49:56,647 --> 00:49:57,388
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes.

715
00:49:57,368 --> 00:50:02,796
[SPEAKER_24]: If there is a moral case for low taxation, why are you proposing such small reductions in tax?

716
00:50:04,303 --> 00:50:06,012
[SPEAKER_25]: Because I'm a practical man.

717
00:50:06,160 --> 00:50:09,044
[SPEAKER_25]: and because I want to do what I believe is right for the country.

718
00:50:09,585 --> 00:50:28,675
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, I think that we have to spend quite a lot of money in future on some of the important things, particularly hospitals and schools, because we are the fourth richest country in the world and it's about time we had a standard of education and a standard of healthcare that matched that fact.

719
00:50:28,655 --> 00:50:31,620
[SPEAKER_25]: Now, in order to do that, I think we need to change the system.

720
00:50:31,700 --> 00:50:47,985
[SPEAKER_25]: I think we need to trust doctors and nurses and trust teachers and not have all these targets, not have the command and control system that we have now in health and education, and we'd make changes to get real value for the taxpayers' money, but the money's needed as well.

721
00:50:48,326 --> 00:50:55,557
[SPEAKER_25]: So we've put forward our plans, we've said, where we would identify the waste and cut it out, and the choice between

722
00:50:55,537 --> 00:50:57,559
[SPEAKER_25]: for the country next week is this.

723
00:50:57,579 --> 00:51:07,709
[SPEAKER_25]: £4 billion of tax cuts from the Conservatives, £10 or £11 billion of tax increases from Labour, which every independent expert said they'd need.

724
00:51:08,189 --> 00:51:14,035
[SPEAKER_25]: That's a difference of about £1,000 for a typical family in the country, so it's a pretty sizeable amount.

725
00:51:14,135 --> 00:51:21,882
[SPEAKER_30]: Would, a simple question, if you're returned as a government and you're Prime Minister, would your government increase

726
00:51:21,862 --> 00:51:28,435
[SPEAKER_30]: the percentage of the nation's wealth created each year that's taken in tax, leave it the same or reduce it?

727
00:51:28,716 --> 00:51:30,079
[SPEAKER_30]: You're talking about the tax burden?

728
00:51:30,139 --> 00:51:34,087
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm talking about the amount of money the government receives from all of us here in tax.

729
00:51:34,207 --> 00:51:35,389
[SPEAKER_25]: As a proportion of income?

730
00:51:35,490 --> 00:51:35,750
[SPEAKER_25]: Yes.

731
00:51:35,951 --> 00:51:36,692
[SPEAKER_25]: Of national income?

732
00:51:36,732 --> 00:51:36,953
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes.

733
00:51:37,073 --> 00:51:38,115
[SPEAKER_25]: It would go up.

734
00:51:38,095 --> 00:51:40,659
[SPEAKER_25]: It would go up, so taxes would go up under the Tories.

735
00:51:40,719 --> 00:51:41,821
[SPEAKER_25]: No, we'd cut taxes.

736
00:51:41,841 --> 00:51:43,223
[SPEAKER_25]: The tax rates wouldn't go up.

737
00:51:43,423 --> 00:51:44,625
[SPEAKER_25]: But we'd be paying more money.

738
00:51:44,665 --> 00:51:45,306
[SPEAKER_25]: What's the difference?

739
00:51:45,326 --> 00:51:55,221
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, what always happens, you know this perfectly well, David, what always happens as an economy grows is that with the same tax rates, the proportion of national income that's taken in tax goes up.

740
00:51:55,241 --> 00:52:00,188
[SPEAKER_25]: It would go up much less with a Conservative government than it would with a Labour government.

741
00:52:00,168 --> 00:52:24,387
[SPEAKER_25]: and we would cut taxes, cut taxes across the range in our first budget, cut taxes for people trying to get a foot on the housing ladder by raising the stamp duty threshold to a quarter of a million pounds, help people who want to save for their pensions by giving them an extra £10 of tax relief for every £100 they put in their pension fund, and cut taxes for pensioners by giving them a 50% discount on their council tax bill

742
00:52:24,367 --> 00:52:29,113
[SPEAKER_25]: for every household where every adult is over 65, up to a limit of 500 pounds.

743
00:52:29,133 --> 00:52:36,742
[SPEAKER_25]: So every age range in the population would be helped by what we are proposing in tax cuts in our first budget.

744
00:52:36,762 --> 00:52:44,431
[SPEAKER_30]: Do you have an ideal figure of what you think the tax take should be for a Western economy in the beginning of the 21st century?

745
00:52:44,451 --> 00:52:47,455
[SPEAKER_30]: Do you have a target, since you make a moral issue about tax?

746
00:52:47,435 --> 00:52:51,383
[SPEAKER_25]: No, I don't have a particular figure in mind.

747
00:52:51,623 --> 00:53:02,625
[SPEAKER_25]: We do say that it would be lower, it would be 40% under a Conservative government after a period of time as compared to 42% under Labour.

748
00:53:02,605 --> 00:53:16,179
[SPEAKER_25]: and you've always got to balance the need for proper public services with the need for a low-tax economy which will encourage people to use their hard work, their skills, their energy, their enterprise to the full.

749
00:53:16,479 --> 00:53:20,864
[SPEAKER_25]: And it's a balanced judgment that you have to make at each budget every year.

750
00:53:21,064 --> 00:53:21,565
[SPEAKER_25]: Okay.

751
00:53:21,585 --> 00:53:24,868
[SPEAKER_30]: As long as you promise not to talk about bullying again, you can have just one quick comment.

752
00:53:25,409 --> 00:53:26,330
[SPEAKER_30]: Bullying is very important.

753
00:53:26,410 --> 00:53:28,512
[SPEAKER_30]: No, no, no, but he's already asked this question before.

754
00:53:28,492 --> 00:53:30,174
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, it'd give you continuity throughout the show.

755
00:53:30,194 --> 00:53:30,895
[SPEAKER_05]: No, no, I don't want that.

756
00:53:31,235 --> 00:53:31,876
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

757
00:53:32,216 --> 00:53:35,520
[SPEAKER_05]: You're talking about taxes and you've talked about education and discipline in schools.

758
00:53:35,961 --> 00:53:41,668
[SPEAKER_05]: Would you ring-fence some of the money you raise through taxes to make sure that bullying is actually...

759
00:53:42,529 --> 00:53:43,210
[SPEAKER_05]: Sorry about that.

760
00:53:43,230 --> 00:53:54,163
[SPEAKER_05]: ..is actually dealt with so that we've got funding in there so that 15 to 20 children every year aren't committing suicide in our school system because there is nothing there for them that's compulsory and that's standardised?

761
00:53:54,183 --> 00:53:54,824
[SPEAKER_30]: Sorry about that.

762
00:53:54,844 --> 00:53:54,944
[SPEAKER_25]: Good.

763
00:53:54,964 --> 00:53:56,085
[SPEAKER_30]: OK, no apologies.

764
00:53:56,065 --> 00:54:01,195
[SPEAKER_25]: It is a very, very important question and bullying in our schools is a hugely important problem.

765
00:54:01,676 --> 00:54:06,665
[SPEAKER_25]: It's a part of the discipline problem which I was talking about earlier.

766
00:54:07,046 --> 00:54:13,679
[SPEAKER_25]: And we have to tackle this if our children are to get the decent chance in life that they need.

767
00:54:13,779 --> 00:54:14,661
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm very lucky.

768
00:54:15,022 --> 00:54:16,825
[SPEAKER_25]: I come from an ordinary family but I went to a school

769
00:54:16,805 --> 00:54:19,610
[SPEAKER_25]: a good state school, and I've benefited enormously from that.

770
00:54:19,630 --> 00:54:23,597
[SPEAKER_25]: And I want every child in this country to have the same kind of chance that I had.

771
00:54:23,697 --> 00:54:26,942
[SPEAKER_25]: So, to come directly to your question, if you give...

772
00:54:26,962 --> 00:54:29,346
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm not sure that you need to ring-fence the money.

773
00:54:29,827 --> 00:54:40,365
[SPEAKER_25]: If you give the head teachers the power to enforce discipline, what happens at the moment is if a head wants to exclude someone from school, someone who's been guilty of bullying, for example,

774
00:54:40,345 --> 00:54:46,133
[SPEAKER_25]: That headteacher can be second-guessed by a panel who take the appeal.

775
00:54:46,454 --> 00:54:47,976
[SPEAKER_25]: They may know little about the school.

776
00:54:48,276 --> 00:54:49,999
[SPEAKER_25]: They will know nothing about the child.

777
00:54:50,299 --> 00:54:52,262
[SPEAKER_25]: And if they override the headteacher...

778
00:54:52,422 --> 00:54:53,704
[SPEAKER_25]: The Tory idea, that, wasn't it?

779
00:54:53,724 --> 00:54:55,186
[SPEAKER_25]: They undermine the headteachers.

780
00:54:55,206 --> 00:54:55,867
[SPEAKER_25]: The Tory idea.

781
00:54:56,027 --> 00:54:57,049
[SPEAKER_25]: And we learn from our mistakes.

782
00:54:57,069 --> 00:54:57,590
[SPEAKER_25]: All right, good.

783
00:54:57,610 --> 00:55:00,173
[SPEAKER_30]: We learn from our mistakes.

784
00:55:00,193 --> 00:55:00,534
[SPEAKER_30]: That's the point.

785
00:55:00,554 --> 00:55:03,398
[SPEAKER_30]: And you... Just a note, very briefly now, and then we'll move on.

786
00:55:03,418 --> 00:55:03,598
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes.

787
00:55:03,859 --> 00:55:04,800
[SPEAKER_30]: Just quickly, if you would.

788
00:55:05,118 --> 00:55:05,499
[SPEAKER_45]: Thank you.

789
00:55:05,619 --> 00:55:14,311
[SPEAKER_45]: The current government refuses to implement the Royal Commission on long-term care because it says the country can't afford it.

790
00:55:15,152 --> 00:55:17,094
[SPEAKER_45]: Now, you're proposing tax cuts.

791
00:55:17,715 --> 00:55:34,298
[SPEAKER_45]: Does that mean to say that the Conservative Party won't implement the recommendations either, even bearing in mind that recently the Commons Select Committee on Healthcare said that it should be implemented?

792
00:55:34,430 --> 00:55:45,553
[SPEAKER_25]: Right, well it's a very serious problem and one of the worries which older people have is that they will have to sell their home in order to pay for the costs of long-term care.

793
00:55:45,989 --> 00:55:48,593
[SPEAKER_45]: That's not the thing I'm talking about.

794
00:55:48,613 --> 00:56:07,424
[SPEAKER_45]: I'm talking about the fact that when people receive care from social services in their homes or in residential care or in nursing homes, they have to pay for the personal care, being helped to wash and dress and go to the toilet.

795
00:56:07,825 --> 00:56:10,950
[SPEAKER_45]: That's got nothing to do with having to sell your house to pay for a place.

796
00:56:10,930 --> 00:56:13,733
[SPEAKER_25]: OK, well, I misunderstood the question, and you're quite right.

797
00:56:14,114 --> 00:56:14,695
[SPEAKER_25]: There is...

798
00:56:15,095 --> 00:56:17,238
[SPEAKER_25]: I think there are questions to be asked.

799
00:56:17,258 --> 00:56:26,389
[SPEAKER_25]: This is about the dividing line between nursing care and personal care, because nursing care is free and personal care isn't.

800
00:56:26,889 --> 00:56:35,099
[SPEAKER_25]: And I think there are real questions to be asked about the dividing line between the two, and we would look again at the dividing line between the two.

801
00:56:35,299 --> 00:56:37,963
[SPEAKER_30]: OK, let me take a quick question from Kirsty MacIver, please.

802
00:56:38,063 --> 00:56:39,064
[SPEAKER_30]: Kirsty MacIver.

803
00:56:40,883 --> 00:56:48,843
[SPEAKER_41]: This is the idea that you'll pay towards people who go into private healthcare.

804
00:56:48,923 --> 00:56:53,475
[SPEAKER_30]: What do you see?

805
00:56:54,974 --> 00:57:01,663
[SPEAKER_25]: There are lots of people who go for private healthcare at the moment who can't afford it.

806
00:57:01,823 --> 00:57:12,617
[SPEAKER_25]: There was an item on the news this evening about someone who had to sell their home in order to get the private care they needed because they had to wait so long for their treatment under the NHS.

807
00:57:12,637 --> 00:57:15,381
[SPEAKER_25]: These are all people who've paid their taxes.

808
00:57:15,801 --> 00:57:18,805
[SPEAKER_25]: They've paid towards the cost of their NHS treatment.

809
00:57:18,785 --> 00:57:20,528
[SPEAKER_30]: The poorest won't get advantage of this.

810
00:57:20,568 --> 00:57:21,950
[SPEAKER_30]: People really can't afford anything.

811
00:57:22,451 --> 00:57:25,095
[SPEAKER_30]: You'll be giving a bit of money, as I understand it.

812
00:57:25,235 --> 00:57:30,604
[SPEAKER_25]: We'll be giving half the cost of an NHS operation if someone wants to go private.

813
00:57:31,125 --> 00:57:33,649
[SPEAKER_25]: And these are all people who've paid their taxes.

814
00:57:33,709 --> 00:57:36,173
[SPEAKER_25]: They've paid for the cost of their NHS operation.

815
00:57:36,594 --> 00:57:41,361
[SPEAKER_25]: They're lessening the NHS waiting lists by going into the private sector.

816
00:57:41,381 --> 00:57:45,568
[SPEAKER_25]: I think it's only fair that they should get a proportion of what it would have cost the NHS after all.

817
00:57:45,548 --> 00:57:54,405
[SPEAKER_25]: It's a good deal for the NHS, because instead of having to pay for the whole of the cost of the operation, they're only paying a contribution, a half of it, and that person goes off the waiting list.

818
00:57:54,425 --> 00:57:55,487
[SPEAKER_25]: Would you do the same for schools?

819
00:57:55,908 --> 00:57:56,930
[SPEAKER_25]: People wanting to go private?

820
00:57:57,111 --> 00:57:57,531
[SPEAKER_25]: No.

821
00:57:57,872 --> 00:57:58,954
[SPEAKER_25]: What we would do for schools...

822
00:57:59,014 --> 00:57:59,816
[SPEAKER_25]: Same principle, isn't it?

823
00:57:59,856 --> 00:58:03,022
[SPEAKER_25]: It's not quite, because we're very practical about this, we're very pragmatic.

824
00:58:03,042 --> 00:58:04,184
[SPEAKER_25]: There's a difference between the two.

825
00:58:04,545 --> 00:58:06,088
[SPEAKER_25]: The problem in health

826
00:58:06,068 --> 00:58:10,172
[SPEAKER_25]: is overwhelmingly one of capacity, so we want to encourage more capacity.

827
00:58:11,133 --> 00:58:12,755
[SPEAKER_25]: The problem in education is a bit different.

828
00:58:12,775 --> 00:58:14,977
[SPEAKER_25]: You don't have children on waiting lists in general.

829
00:58:15,017 --> 00:58:17,600
[SPEAKER_25]: I know there are some in London at the moment, and that's a disgrace.

830
00:58:17,920 --> 00:58:21,404
[SPEAKER_25]: But in general, children are not on waiting lists to go to school.

831
00:58:21,424 --> 00:58:35,518
[SPEAKER_25]: It's a question of choice and quality and standards, and so we would encourage... What we say is, if private sector can provide education at the same cost as the state, then children and parents should be able to choose that private school.

832
00:58:35,498 --> 00:58:37,240
[SPEAKER_25]: But only if it's the same cost as the state.

833
00:58:37,260 --> 00:58:38,861
[SPEAKER_30]: I have to stop you there, Mr. Howard.

834
00:58:38,881 --> 00:58:43,585
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm sorry, Jack Skillen wasn't able to ask his question, which is, are you thinking what we are thinking?

835
00:58:44,146 --> 00:58:45,207
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, let me just say one thing.

836
00:58:45,227 --> 00:58:45,787
[SPEAKER_30]: No, you can't.

837
00:58:45,908 --> 00:58:47,049
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm sorry, your time's up.

838
00:58:47,089 --> 00:58:48,090
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you very much indeed.

839
00:58:59,780 --> 00:59:02,603
[SPEAKER_30]: Well, all right.

840
00:59:03,123 --> 00:59:11,007
[SPEAKER_30]: Finally, tonight, the man who wants to lead the Labour Party to a third victory after eight years at number 10, the Prime Minister, Tony Blair.

841
00:59:19,846 --> 00:59:20,948
[SPEAKER_30]: Hello.

842
00:59:20,968 --> 00:59:24,054
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr Blair, your first question comes from Christopher Jones, please.

843
00:59:24,354 --> 00:59:24,595
[SPEAKER_04]: Hello.

844
00:59:25,616 --> 00:59:34,733
[SPEAKER_04]: Why did you consider it inappropriate to give the Cabinet the benefit of the Attorney General's full opinion regarding the legality of military action against Iraq?

845
00:59:42,070 --> 00:59:49,599
[SPEAKER_22]: because we had the Attorney General there at Cabinet, and he was able to tell people his opinion, explain his reasoning, answer any questions that they had.

846
00:59:50,360 --> 00:59:57,710
[SPEAKER_22]: And in the end, remember, for the past few days, it's been said that the Attorney General advised that it was illegal to go to war.

847
00:59:57,810 --> 00:59:58,170
[SPEAKER_22]: He didn't.

848
00:59:58,731 --> 00:59:59,712
[SPEAKER_22]: He advised it was lawful.

849
01:00:00,293 --> 01:00:09,124
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, I totally understand why there will be people in this audience tonight who very, very strongly disagree with my decision to take this country to war in Iran.

850
01:00:09,627 --> 01:00:12,430
[SPEAKER_22]: OK. All I can say to you is this.

851
01:00:12,470 --> 01:00:17,756
[SPEAKER_22]: It's not a matter of the Attorney-General's advice, because it's been shown that he advised it was lawful.

852
01:00:18,297 --> 01:00:20,439
[SPEAKER_22]: Neither is the matter of misusing the intelligence.

853
01:00:20,479 --> 01:00:21,901
[SPEAKER_22]: There have been four inquiries into that.

854
01:00:22,481 --> 01:00:26,065
[SPEAKER_22]: It is, however, a question of a difficult decision I had to take.

855
01:00:26,766 --> 01:00:30,130
[SPEAKER_22]: Was it better to leave Saddam in power or put him in prison?

856
01:00:30,390 --> 01:00:32,833
[SPEAKER_22]: I think it was better to put him in prison.

857
01:00:36,307 --> 01:00:40,853
[SPEAKER_30]: Christopher Jones' question isn't about the Attorney General's final decision.

858
01:00:41,154 --> 01:00:48,283
[SPEAKER_30]: It's about this document, which you have been avoiding publishing for the past two years, and were forced to publish at half past eleven this morning, suddenly.

859
01:00:48,584 --> 01:00:50,667
[SPEAKER_30]: And it's, did this document go before Cabinet?

860
01:00:51,147 --> 01:00:52,009
[SPEAKER_30]: And if not, why not?

861
01:00:52,089 --> 01:00:54,232
[SPEAKER_30]: And did this document go before the House of Commons?

862
01:00:54,452 --> 01:01:03,985
[SPEAKER_30]: With all its hesitations, reservations, explanations, so that your backbench MPs had a chance to study the whole background to the legal decision that he then made.

863
01:01:03,965 --> 01:01:07,948
[SPEAKER_22]: In respect of Parliament, the Attorney General's advice is never published to Parliament.

864
01:01:08,028 --> 01:01:10,431
[SPEAKER_22]: It's been published, I think, three times over the last hundred years.

865
01:01:10,471 --> 01:01:11,331
[SPEAKER_22]: And yet it's now.

866
01:01:11,351 --> 01:01:11,592
[SPEAKER_22]: Exactly.

867
01:01:11,612 --> 01:01:12,332
[SPEAKER_22]: Published to everybody.

868
01:01:12,512 --> 01:01:13,753
[SPEAKER_22]: Exactly, because it's been leaked.

869
01:01:14,014 --> 01:01:15,875
[SPEAKER_22]: And therefore, you might as well have the full opinion.

870
01:01:16,376 --> 01:01:24,423
[SPEAKER_22]: In respect of Cabinet, the reason why we didn't give people the advice is we actually had the Attorney General there in Cabinet.

871
01:01:24,723 --> 01:01:26,024
[SPEAKER_22]: And there isn't any doubt about it.

872
01:01:26,044 --> 01:01:28,066
[SPEAKER_22]: And was all this ground covered?

873
01:01:28,086 --> 01:01:33,010
[SPEAKER_22]: The Attorney General went through his reasoning and explained to Cabinet why, in his view,

874
01:01:33,091 --> 01:01:36,658
[SPEAKER_22]: there was a reasonable case that could be made that the action was lawful.

875
01:01:36,959 --> 01:01:38,041
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, that is what has happened.

876
01:01:38,381 --> 01:01:41,668
[SPEAKER_22]: And look, as I say, in the end, you can frame this any way you want.

877
01:01:42,069 --> 01:01:46,818
[SPEAKER_22]: But the question was, when we were faced with the situation, I think it's important people understand this.

878
01:01:46,898 --> 01:01:50,846
[SPEAKER_22]: Back in March 2003, we were trying to get a second United Nations resolution.

879
01:01:50,866 --> 01:01:52,028
[SPEAKER_22]: We couldn't get one.

880
01:01:52,008 --> 01:01:55,555
[SPEAKER_22]: because France said they would not accept any resolution with an ultimatum to Saddam.

881
01:01:56,036 --> 01:01:57,539
[SPEAKER_22]: In the end, therefore, I had to decide.

882
01:01:57,619 --> 01:02:01,026
[SPEAKER_22]: We had 250,000 UK and US troops down there.

883
01:02:01,046 --> 01:02:02,889
[SPEAKER_22]: It was a tough decision, it was a difficult one.

884
01:02:03,250 --> 01:02:05,855
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't expect people, everyone, to agree with it.

885
01:02:06,256 --> 01:02:09,241
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't disrespect people who take a completely different point of view.

886
01:02:09,602 --> 01:02:14,151
[SPEAKER_22]: But I'm afraid this was an occasion, there was no fence to sit on, I had to take the decision and I took it.

887
01:02:14,131 --> 01:02:15,593
[SPEAKER_30]: OK. Christopher Jones, you asked a question.

888
01:02:15,613 --> 01:02:16,414
[SPEAKER_30]: You want to come back on that?

889
01:02:16,434 --> 01:02:36,443
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, the thing I don't understand is, given the importance of the decision, and I take your point that the Attorney-General was there in Cabinet, but I read that opinion today and it makes interesting reading, and I just can't understand why the Cabinet, who are a bunch of clever individuals who you rely on, weren't given the opportunity to see that document as well as question the Attorney-General.

890
01:02:36,423 --> 01:02:38,566
[SPEAKER_22]: But because they actually had the Attorney General there in person.

891
01:02:38,986 --> 01:02:46,817
[SPEAKER_22]: And therefore, in a sense, what was important was that he was able to take them through the reasoning in person and say to them...

892
01:02:46,837 --> 01:02:47,398
[SPEAKER_04]: But not that piece of paper?

893
01:02:47,418 --> 01:02:50,862
[SPEAKER_22]: No, because he was there able to explain it orally himself.

894
01:02:51,283 --> 01:02:56,189
[SPEAKER_22]: And look, in the end, the only question is, did the Attorney General advise that the war was lawful?

895
01:02:56,250 --> 01:02:56,610
[SPEAKER_22]: He did.

896
01:02:57,171 --> 01:03:00,355
[SPEAKER_22]: But in the end, the decision about this

897
01:03:01,381 --> 01:03:03,323
[SPEAKER_22]: It isn't really to do with the Attorney General.

898
01:03:03,464 --> 01:03:05,867
[SPEAKER_22]: It was a political decision that had to be taken.

899
01:03:06,688 --> 01:03:16,340
[SPEAKER_22]: Look, you know, I've been over this ground I don't know how many times in the last couple of years, and I totally understand why some people feel that this was the wrong decision to take.

900
01:03:16,801 --> 01:03:20,465
[SPEAKER_22]: But I happen to believe, for the reasons that I gave, it was the right decision.

901
01:03:20,486 --> 01:03:21,006
[SPEAKER_22]: All right.

902
01:03:21,026 --> 01:03:22,108
[SPEAKER_22]: Let's hear from you, sir.

903
01:03:22,748 --> 01:03:27,895
[SPEAKER_05]: Did any member of the Cabinet ask to read the Attorney General's guidance?

904
01:03:28,448 --> 01:03:33,318
[SPEAKER_22]: No, no member of the Cabinet asked for it because the Attorney General was there and able to take them through it personally.

905
01:03:33,939 --> 01:03:34,360
[SPEAKER_22]: You, Madam?

906
01:03:34,520 --> 01:03:38,849
[SPEAKER_01]: Was the Attorney General present at the Cabinet meeting before or after he changed his mind?

907
01:03:39,430 --> 01:03:40,973
[SPEAKER_22]: He didn't...

908
01:03:45,357 --> 01:03:46,679
[SPEAKER_22]: With respect, he didn't change his mind.

909
01:03:46,699 --> 01:03:51,766
[SPEAKER_22]: The 7th of March advice was, which has now been published, was that it was lawful.

910
01:03:52,387 --> 01:04:04,085
[SPEAKER_22]: And when he came to Cabinet, he explained, as he says in his advice, of course it's better to have a second resolution, but if you can't get one, then the action is still lawful for the reasons that he gave.

911
01:04:05,166 --> 01:04:06,188
[SPEAKER_22]: All right, the woman here.

912
01:04:06,208 --> 01:04:09,553
[SPEAKER_20]: I think it's very interesting that you decide to describe your decision as a political decision.

913
01:04:09,593 --> 01:04:14,520
[SPEAKER_20]: What it was was a political decision to support your best mate, George Bush.

914
01:04:19,580 --> 01:04:24,472
[SPEAKER_20]: The other point is you always say, oh, it's perfectly OK because Saddam Hussein is a really nasty guy.

915
01:04:24,732 --> 01:04:26,176
[SPEAKER_20]: Clearly, that is self-evidently true.

916
01:04:26,296 --> 01:04:27,579
[SPEAKER_20]: It is also an academic point.

917
01:04:27,639 --> 01:04:33,212
[SPEAKER_20]: The reality is George Bush would have invaded and removed Saddam Hussein without your support.

918
01:04:33,693 --> 01:04:35,277
[SPEAKER_22]: Oh, first of all...

919
01:04:38,243 --> 01:04:44,077
[SPEAKER_22]: It wasn't an academic point for the hundreds of thousands of Iraqis who lost their lives under Saddam Hussein.

920
01:04:44,097 --> 01:04:45,059
[SPEAKER_22]: It was important for them.

921
01:04:45,821 --> 01:04:49,610
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, you may say that I took the action simply for America.

922
01:04:49,630 --> 01:04:49,951
[SPEAKER_22]: I didn't.

923
01:04:50,111 --> 01:04:52,497
[SPEAKER_22]: I took it because I believed it was in the interest of this country.

924
01:04:53,098 --> 01:04:56,286
[SPEAKER_22]: If we had backed away and left Saddam in power,

925
01:04:56,266 --> 01:05:04,418
[SPEAKER_22]: stronger because we had backed away, I think that would have been bad for the security of our region and our world and therefore of this country.

926
01:05:04,719 --> 01:05:11,429
[SPEAKER_22]: As I say, you can conduct this debate in whichever way you want, but I took that decision in good faith.

927
01:05:11,809 --> 01:05:15,896
[SPEAKER_22]: Sometimes, when you are sitting in my seat as Prime Minister, you have to take the decision.

928
01:05:16,356 --> 01:05:17,498
[SPEAKER_22]: That is the decision I took.

929
01:05:18,608 --> 01:05:21,993
[SPEAKER_20]: Prime Minister but it is your job to make the right decision and you made the wrong one.

930
01:05:22,113 --> 01:05:31,766
[SPEAKER_22]: Well that's your view but it's interesting isn't it that today we actually have a democratic government being formed in Iraq.

931
01:05:31,786 --> 01:05:36,853
[SPEAKER_22]: Isn't that something we should actually be proud that we helped bring about?

932
01:05:37,745 --> 01:05:42,853
[SPEAKER_14]: As I understand it, the Attorney General expressed reservations about the legality of the war.

933
01:05:43,514 --> 01:05:45,136
[SPEAKER_14]: Why not just give the full legal opinion?

934
01:05:45,637 --> 01:05:49,282
[SPEAKER_14]: Because many MPs might have changed their mind under those circumstances.

935
01:05:49,623 --> 01:05:56,273
[SPEAKER_14]: The other point is, when you presented your evidence to the House of Commons, you said it was authoritative and full evidence.

936
01:05:56,353 --> 01:05:57,194
[SPEAKER_14]: I can't remember the words.

937
01:05:57,534 --> 01:06:00,198
[SPEAKER_14]: Yet the intelligence said to you it was sporadic and patchy.

938
01:06:00,519 --> 01:06:01,460
[SPEAKER_14]: That is a lie.

939
01:06:01,520 --> 01:06:06,047
[SPEAKER_14]: You lie to this country and that's why we can't support you at the following election.

940
01:06:10,567 --> 01:06:10,960
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you.

941
01:06:13,385 --> 01:06:15,007
[SPEAKER_22]: You're going to have to make your decision about that.

942
01:06:15,447 --> 01:06:25,118
[SPEAKER_22]: Before you make that decision, though, the interesting thing about the intelligence, and there have been four inquiries into this, all of which have found the same thing, that I acted in good faith in relation to the intelligence.

943
01:06:25,138 --> 01:06:35,890
[SPEAKER_22]: But before you make that decision, you can actually go onto the website, I think it's with the Butler Report, and you can read the judgments of the Joint Intelligence Committee about Saddam Hussein and weapons of mass destruction.

944
01:06:36,230 --> 01:06:43,138
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, I just ask you, before you make that allegation again, go and read that and then tell me there was no evidence at all before me.

945
01:06:43,118 --> 01:06:50,859
[SPEAKER_14]: Why don't you have a full independent inquiry answering all the questions rather than just specific worded questions which you decide upon?

946
01:06:51,782 --> 01:06:53,787
[SPEAKER_22]: Do you know how many inquiries we've had?

947
01:06:54,256 --> 01:06:57,099
[SPEAKER_22]: You decide the wording every time.

948
01:06:58,321 --> 01:07:03,227
[SPEAKER_22]: The Hutton inquiry was a six-month inquiry.

949
01:07:03,487 --> 01:07:07,872
[SPEAKER_22]: The Foreign Affairs Committee decided their own terms of reference, so did the Intelligence Committee.

950
01:07:08,052 --> 01:07:13,038
[SPEAKER_22]: We have had four inquiries, we could have another four.

951
01:07:13,439 --> 01:07:16,062
[SPEAKER_22]: And frankly, after that, we could have another four.

952
01:07:16,042 --> 01:07:17,183
[SPEAKER_14]: full public inquiry.

953
01:07:17,984 --> 01:07:19,305
[SPEAKER_30]: We've already had one.

954
01:07:19,325 --> 01:07:23,629
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr Blair, you mentioned the Butler inquiry and cited it in your own defence.

955
01:07:24,229 --> 01:07:25,891
[SPEAKER_30]: Can I just quote you from Butler?

956
01:07:26,951 --> 01:07:44,867
[SPEAKER_30]: He said that the intelligence, which as the young man said correctly, was described by the JIC as sporadic and patchy, that the dossier you produced in September went to the outer limits of that intelligence and that by calling it extensive, detailed and authoritative, you may have reinforced that impression.

957
01:07:44,847 --> 01:07:54,320
[SPEAKER_30]: isn't that saying, not that you lied, but that you exaggerated, you over-egged, you misled, you sailed a bit close to the wind when you put across this intelligence to the British public?

958
01:07:54,440 --> 01:07:59,507
[SPEAKER_22]: What I do accept, frankly, in retrospect, is that it would have been better just to have published the Joint Intelligence Committee reports.

959
01:07:59,887 --> 01:08:02,711
[SPEAKER_22]: I think that would have been a better way of doing it, because then you wouldn't have had this argument.

960
01:08:02,972 --> 01:08:05,555
[SPEAKER_22]: And that's why I said to this young man here that...

961
01:08:05,575 --> 01:08:06,917
[SPEAKER_30]: It doesn't answer my question, that.

962
01:08:07,798 --> 01:08:10,001
[SPEAKER_30]: You said it was extensive, detailed and authoritative.

963
01:08:10,021 --> 01:08:10,602
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes, it was.

964
01:08:10,582 --> 01:08:11,704
[SPEAKER_30]: you off for saying that?

965
01:08:11,724 --> 01:08:13,928
[SPEAKER_30]: And you keep saying perhaps I shouldn't have said anything at all.

966
01:08:13,948 --> 01:08:16,091
[SPEAKER_30]: Do you mean you were wrong to say that about it?

967
01:08:16,211 --> 01:08:16,852
[SPEAKER_22]: No, I don't mean that.

968
01:08:16,872 --> 01:08:17,894
[SPEAKER_22]: But you accept it wasn't that?

969
01:08:17,914 --> 01:08:27,510
[SPEAKER_22]: What I mean is that Butler said, and I think this is right and I've accepted this, because I'm not saying there haven't been mistakes made and things for which I have to take responsibility.

970
01:08:27,490 --> 01:08:47,136
[SPEAKER_22]: but I think that in the end what would have been better in retrospect is just to have published the raw intelligence and then people could have seen exactly what the Joint Intelligence Committee actually said to me and that's why I say to you and to anybody here or anybody listening to the program you can go and read the intelligence I got and then make up your own mind as to whether I'm a liar or not.

971
01:08:47,116 --> 01:08:58,501
[SPEAKER_08]: Mr Blair, the whole perception of where we are with yourself at the moment is, you come along, you tell us in 1997 that you're going to be totally transparent, whiter than white.

972
01:08:58,521 --> 01:09:06,137
[SPEAKER_08]: We've had you telling us dossiers that you've got produced to get them past the Labour Party, to get them past the Parliamentary Labour Party.

973
01:09:06,117 --> 01:09:11,065
[SPEAKER_08]: You've bounced them in with documents that have been sorted out on settees, no doubt, and here we are today.

974
01:09:11,085 --> 01:09:16,895
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, I have to say, you keep saying to us over the last two days that you will make the difficult decisions.

975
01:09:16,915 --> 01:09:17,415
[SPEAKER_08]: You will do.

976
01:09:17,436 --> 01:09:18,698
[SPEAKER_08]: That's what you're paid to do.

977
01:09:19,238 --> 01:09:25,088
[SPEAKER_08]: What you're also paid to do is listen to the experts, listen to the advice that you're being given, and make an informed decision.

978
01:09:25,068 --> 01:09:29,595
[SPEAKER_08]: I have to say, I certainly don't think you are transparent from what I hear at the moment.

979
01:09:29,676 --> 01:09:35,104
[SPEAKER_08]: That's without the Mandelson sagas, the indulges, and that is where you are battling now.

980
01:09:35,345 --> 01:09:46,723
[SPEAKER_08]: You are fighting a rearguard action on the transparency that you told us that when we cleared the other lot out in 97, you were going to be the white man in white armour to come along and make it all whiter than white.

981
01:09:46,884 --> 01:09:47,785
[SPEAKER_22]: You haven't done it.

982
01:09:47,765 --> 01:09:51,893
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, why don't we, instead of dealing with perception, we deal with the reality.

983
01:09:52,354 --> 01:09:59,047
[SPEAKER_22]: And if you doubt the position that I'm saying on the intelligence, as I say, the great thing is you can go and read it for yourself and make up your own mind about that.

984
01:09:59,468 --> 01:10:04,778
[SPEAKER_22]: But I like to think that also there are certain changes we've made in this country that we can be proud of as a government.

985
01:10:04,758 --> 01:10:05,941
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't disagree with that.

986
01:10:05,981 --> 01:10:20,421
[SPEAKER_08]: Where I do disagree with you fundamentally is you have committed yourself to support Mr Bush, you have then got to come back here, you have got to get it passed,

987
01:10:20,401 --> 01:10:31,015
[SPEAKER_08]: left-wing side of your party, with all due respect, you struggled to get it passed, you lost cabinet ministers over it, and here we are today, we have dragged this out of you today.

988
01:10:31,035 --> 01:10:33,438
[SPEAKER_22]: I think you have made the point.

989
01:10:33,539 --> 01:10:40,027
[SPEAKER_22]: I think that is a point that is worth responding head-on to.

990
01:10:40,388 --> 01:10:45,835
[SPEAKER_22]: In the end, yes, I did have to struggle very hard to get this through.

991
01:10:45,815 --> 01:10:48,501
[SPEAKER_22]: But the reason I did it was because I thought it was the right thing to do.

992
01:10:48,541 --> 01:10:54,092
[SPEAKER_22]: I didn't take this on myself for reasons just because I thought, let's give myself a really hard time for a couple of years.

993
01:10:54,513 --> 01:10:56,778
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, sorry, I think you've made your case.

994
01:10:56,798 --> 01:10:57,900
[SPEAKER_22]: No, that's a reasonable enough point.

995
01:10:58,181 --> 01:11:05,616
[SPEAKER_22]: All I say to you on the other stuff is, if you go back and have a look at what I read, then, you know, drop me a line and tell me what you think about it afterwards.

996
01:11:05,777 --> 01:11:06,979
[SPEAKER_22]: The woman there in grey.

997
01:11:07,010 --> 01:11:18,984
[SPEAKER_06]: Brian Sedgmore said that you'd pretty much made up your mind after going to speak to George Blair, before you'd even spoken to... George Bush, I think.

998
01:11:19,004 --> 01:11:19,184
[SPEAKER_06]: George...

999
01:11:19,204 --> 01:11:19,324
Sorry.

1000
01:11:19,344 --> 01:11:19,584
[SPEAKER_06]: George Bush.

1001
01:11:19,604 --> 01:11:20,085
[SPEAKER_06]: Freudian slip there.

1002
01:11:20,105 --> 01:11:20,305
[SPEAKER_06]: All right.

1003
01:11:20,325 --> 01:11:20,385
[SPEAKER_06]: OK.

1004
01:11:20,405 --> 01:11:21,567
[SPEAKER_06]: I am... Freudian slip.

1005
01:11:21,587 --> 01:11:21,827
[SPEAKER_06]: All right.

1006
01:11:22,488 --> 01:11:24,830
[SPEAKER_06]: Before you'd even spoken to your own Cabinet.

1007
01:11:25,111 --> 01:11:30,437
[SPEAKER_06]: And as well as that, if you weren't fraudulent, you're grossly negligent, and for that you should be resigning anyway.

1008
01:11:30,897 --> 01:11:33,040
[SPEAKER_22]: Right.

1009
01:11:33,060 --> 01:11:33,220
[SPEAKER_22]: APPLAUSE

1010
01:11:35,866 --> 01:11:43,203
[SPEAKER_22]: First of all, I don't really know how Brian Sedgmore would know, since I don't think he was ever present at any discussion I ever had with George Bush.

1011
01:11:43,223 --> 01:11:45,488
[SPEAKER_22]: In fact, I don't even remember ever discussing it with Brian Sedgmore.

1012
01:11:46,451 --> 01:11:50,119
[SPEAKER_22]: But secondly, you've got to make up your mind about it.

1013
01:11:50,340 --> 01:11:52,204
[SPEAKER_22]: Look, I've taken my decision.

1014
01:11:52,184 --> 01:12:01,156
[SPEAKER_22]: And I would just like to point out to you that in the end, if I'd taken a different decision, that too would have had difficult consequences.

1015
01:12:01,516 --> 01:12:06,482
[SPEAKER_22]: If I decided the course that you want me to take, Saddam Hussein would still be in charge of Iraq today.

1016
01:12:07,023 --> 01:12:09,446
[SPEAKER_22]: People would have been dying in Iraq.

1017
01:12:09,466 --> 01:12:12,410
[SPEAKER_22]: Without television cameras there, it's true, but they were.

1018
01:12:12,771 --> 01:12:15,274
[SPEAKER_22]: Don't speak to me about it, speak to Iraqis about it.

1019
01:12:15,694 --> 01:12:17,677
[SPEAKER_22]: That is why the decision was difficult.

1020
01:12:17,817 --> 01:12:19,339
[SPEAKER_22]: It was difficult to remove him.

1021
01:12:19,319 --> 01:12:20,922
[SPEAKER_22]: It was difficult to leave him there.

1022
01:12:21,203 --> 01:12:23,788
[SPEAKER_30]: I took the decision I thought was right for the country.

1023
01:12:24,770 --> 01:12:26,714
[SPEAKER_30]: I want to move on because I have to watch the clock here.

1024
01:12:27,095 --> 01:12:28,899
[SPEAKER_30]: I will go to another question now.

1025
01:12:31,083 --> 01:12:38,138
[SPEAKER_24]: What new stealth taxis do you plan to introduce first?

1026
01:12:43,737 --> 01:12:49,725
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, I don't plan any, but... Because I just crept up on you, didn't I?

1027
01:12:49,745 --> 01:12:55,032
[SPEAKER_22]: What I would say to you is, this country still remains one of the lowest-taxed countries in the whole of Europe.

1028
01:12:55,052 --> 01:12:58,677
[SPEAKER_22]: Actually, taxes as a proportion of national income is lower than most of the years Margaret Thatcher is in.

1029
01:12:59,238 --> 01:13:02,082
[SPEAKER_22]: And, yes, it's true, we raised national insurance in the last Parliament.

1030
01:13:02,102 --> 01:13:04,164
[SPEAKER_22]: That is absolutely true, to pay for the National Health Service.

1031
01:13:04,285 --> 01:13:05,006
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't regret that.

1032
01:13:05,286 --> 01:13:09,812
[SPEAKER_22]: I think it's good that we are now making improvements in our National Health Service as a result of that investment.

1033
01:13:09,944 --> 01:13:19,345
[SPEAKER_30]: Of course, you did say in your manifesto that expansion would come without any need to increase money, and you never mentioned one less in your manifesto, and you never said you were going to put up money after the election.

1034
01:13:19,365 --> 01:13:25,118
[SPEAKER_30]: You got through that election suggesting to the electorate that you weren't going to increase taxes, let alone put 1% on.

1035
01:13:25,098 --> 01:13:28,002
[SPEAKER_22]: We didn't have to for the commitments that we had, but it's true.

1036
01:13:28,463 --> 01:13:34,231
[SPEAKER_22]: We got the report that said, if you want to get your health service spending up to the European Union average, you're going to have to put more money in.

1037
01:13:34,672 --> 01:13:45,387
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, even with that additional money, I think it's worth just pointing out that the National Health Service, as a result of that, is getting the largest increase investment it's had since it was created.

1038
01:13:45,768 --> 01:13:48,211
[SPEAKER_22]: And I think the National Health Service is improving as a result.

1039
01:13:48,251 --> 01:13:52,758
[SPEAKER_22]: And that is surely better than going down the path of forcing people to take out private medical insurance.

1040
01:13:52,778 --> 01:13:54,480
[SPEAKER_30]: The man in the white shirt back there.

1041
01:13:54,460 --> 01:13:58,144
[SPEAKER_31]: Mr Blair, I think you're very lucky that we have a weak opposition at the moment.

1042
01:14:04,071 --> 01:14:04,372
[SPEAKER_22]: Right.

1043
01:14:05,193 --> 01:14:06,855
[SPEAKER_22]: Do you want to expand on that, or is that it?

1044
01:14:07,576 --> 01:14:13,302
[SPEAKER_22]: I take that as not a compliment, so... OK, the man in the grey shirt there, at the very back row.

1045
01:14:13,543 --> 01:14:14,924
[SPEAKER_30]: No, in the back row there, yes.

1046
01:14:15,105 --> 01:14:17,127
[SPEAKER_48]: Mr Blair... We're untaxed, remember.

1047
01:14:17,950 --> 01:14:25,730
[SPEAKER_48]: Mr Blair, your government has spent an extra £150 billion on the NHS and schools over the last eight years.

1048
01:14:26,191 --> 01:14:31,504
[SPEAKER_48]: What improvements have we seen as a result and can our country afford to waste that kind of money?

1049
01:14:31,703 --> 01:14:32,865
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, I don't believe it is wasted.

1050
01:14:33,385 --> 01:14:35,789
[SPEAKER_22]: Look, I visit schools and hospitals the whole time.

1051
01:14:35,849 --> 01:14:42,017
[SPEAKER_22]: I go in there, I see investment in schools, I see it in new school buildings, in computers, in additional teachers.

1052
01:14:42,098 --> 01:14:43,560
[SPEAKER_22]: I go into the health services.

1053
01:14:43,580 --> 01:14:49,027
[SPEAKER_22]: There's barely a health service site you visit without new buildings being put up, new wards, scanners, extra nurses.

1054
01:14:49,528 --> 01:14:50,269
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't

1055
01:14:50,249 --> 01:14:51,971
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't misunderstand this at all.

1056
01:14:52,031 --> 01:14:54,813
[SPEAKER_22]: There are still big problems that we need to deal with.

1057
01:14:55,193 --> 01:14:58,877
[SPEAKER_22]: But I think if you look at our National Health Service today, we can be proud of it again.

1058
01:14:59,237 --> 01:15:01,459
[SPEAKER_22]: It's improvements happening in the National Health Service.

1059
01:15:01,479 --> 01:15:04,982
[SPEAKER_22]: If you go into the schools, you can see the extra investment in there.

1060
01:15:05,703 --> 01:15:09,846
[SPEAKER_22]: That's on the basis of a strong economy, and that's why I want to keep that investment going in.

1061
01:15:10,206 --> 01:15:14,150
[SPEAKER_22]: And I don't accept the Conservative charge it's all wasted or it's all going on bureaucrats.

1062
01:15:14,610 --> 01:15:19,855
[SPEAKER_22]: Actually, it's going to give our kids a better education and people a better deal on health.

1063
01:15:19,875 --> 01:15:19,935
OK.

1064
01:15:19,915 --> 01:15:22,799
[SPEAKER_30]: The woman there in black.

1065
01:15:23,260 --> 01:15:25,343
[SPEAKER_06]: Can we have some more cleaners, please?

1066
01:15:26,084 --> 01:15:27,847
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes, that's a good point.

1067
01:15:27,887 --> 01:15:30,811
[SPEAKER_30]: And the woman further along in grey.

1068
01:15:30,871 --> 01:15:36,159
[SPEAKER_44]: If the National Health Service has improved, why am I still waiting for eight months for a consultation?

1069
01:15:36,580 --> 01:15:38,062
[SPEAKER_44]: Where's the improvement?

1070
01:15:38,463 --> 01:15:39,945
[SPEAKER_44]: I visit a filthy hospital.

1071
01:15:41,067 --> 01:15:43,591
[SPEAKER_44]: I visited casualty a couple of weeks ago.

1072
01:15:43,831 --> 01:15:44,892
[SPEAKER_44]: There was a four-hour wait.

1073
01:15:45,213 --> 01:15:46,335
[SPEAKER_44]: I don't see an improvement.

1074
01:15:46,355 --> 01:15:47,256
[SPEAKER_44]: Where is it?

1075
01:15:47,354 --> 01:15:51,763
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, I think there is real improvement in the health service.

1076
01:15:51,783 --> 01:15:54,589
[SPEAKER_22]: I'm really sorry if you've been waiting an unacceptable period of time.

1077
01:15:54,609 --> 01:16:07,374
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't know whether there are other people here who have used the health service recently, but I actually think when you go into our healthcare system, I'm not saying everyone, and I'm sorry that you've had a bad experience, but I think, on the whole, people get a very good service out of our National Health Service today.

1078
01:16:07,615 --> 01:16:08,637
[SPEAKER_22]: You, sir.

1079
01:16:08,971 --> 01:16:13,199
[SPEAKER_03]: You certainly should be congratulated about the investment you've made.

1080
01:16:13,219 --> 01:16:16,786
[SPEAKER_03]: You've doubled the figures from 33 to 67 billion this year.

1081
01:16:17,327 --> 01:16:25,022
[SPEAKER_03]: Don't you find it surprising that you're still more likely to catch an infection in a hospital than getting knocked over in the street?

1082
01:16:25,829 --> 01:16:30,358
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, if you're referring to MRSA, it is a real problem and we're tackling it.

1083
01:16:30,458 --> 01:16:33,083
[SPEAKER_22]: We're putting in the matrons and the cleaning that's necessary.

1084
01:16:33,364 --> 01:16:34,586
[SPEAKER_22]: But let me just say this to you.

1085
01:16:35,007 --> 01:16:38,754
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't think that should, as it were, stain the whole of the health service.

1086
01:16:39,796 --> 01:16:47,331
[SPEAKER_22]: I honestly believe that our National Health Service, and I probably visit more hospitals and talk to more people in the health service than any Prime Minister before me,

1087
01:16:47,311 --> 01:16:49,976
[SPEAKER_22]: I think that of course there are real issues and real difficulties.

1088
01:16:50,096 --> 01:16:51,559
[SPEAKER_22]: All healthcare systems have that.

1089
01:16:51,920 --> 01:16:57,590
[SPEAKER_22]: But I think when you go into, for example, an accident and emergency department nowadays, you can see a change and an improvement.

1090
01:16:57,991 --> 01:17:02,620
[SPEAKER_22]: I think for many people who used to wait, for example, you take cardiac care.

1091
01:17:02,600 --> 01:17:06,545
[SPEAKER_22]: people used to wait months and months, years even, to get the treatment that they need.

1092
01:17:06,565 --> 01:17:08,127
[SPEAKER_22]: They don't wait that long anymore.

1093
01:17:08,467 --> 01:17:13,213
[SPEAKER_22]: If you take cataracts, for example, as a result of the changes we've brought in, big change has happened.

1094
01:17:13,553 --> 01:17:21,323
[SPEAKER_22]: In cancer, we now save, literally, I think it's something like 10,000 deaths a year as a result of changes that have been brought in.

1095
01:17:21,343 --> 01:17:27,070
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, I'm not saying it's all perfect, don't misunderstand me, but I am saying it's a darn sight better than what we inherited from the Conservatives in 1997.

1096
01:17:27,130 --> 01:17:29,873
[SPEAKER_30]: No, please, the man in the green shirt, the dark green shirt.

1097
01:17:29,853 --> 01:17:36,322
[SPEAKER_26]: Yes, you're actually putting forward targets on practically everything for timescales.

1098
01:17:36,542 --> 01:17:41,409
[SPEAKER_26]: I can't get an appointment with my local GP unless it's made within 48 hours.

1099
01:17:41,730 --> 01:17:43,792
[SPEAKER_26]: I can't make it three days or four days hence.

1100
01:17:44,273 --> 01:17:49,781
[SPEAKER_26]: I was told that's because they can make their target that everybody gets it within 48 hours.

1101
01:17:51,223 --> 01:17:54,207
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, I'm absolutely astonished at that.

1102
01:17:54,912 --> 01:17:57,637
[SPEAKER_22]: Look, come on, let's be sensible about this.

1103
01:17:58,078 --> 01:18:06,655
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't know about this individual case, obviously, but I would be absolutely astonished if you're saying to your GP, I don't need to see you for four days, and he's insisting he sees you in two.

1104
01:18:06,695 --> 01:18:07,837
[SPEAKER_22]: The reason...

1105
01:18:07,857 --> 01:18:09,881
[SPEAKER_07]: The doctor is asking you to come back in a week.

1106
01:18:10,081 --> 01:18:14,710
[SPEAKER_07]: You can't make the appointment in a week because you're only allowed to make it 48 hours beforehand.

1107
01:18:14,690 --> 01:18:16,494
[SPEAKER_07]: This is my son's appointment last week.

1108
01:18:16,814 --> 01:18:27,576
[SPEAKER_07]: You have to sit on the phone for three hours in the morning, trying to get an appointment, because you're not allowed to ask for the appointment before that, because by making it 48 hours beforehand, they're meeting the government target.

1109
01:18:27,596 --> 01:18:28,458
[SPEAKER_22]: Is this news to you?

1110
01:18:29,019 --> 01:18:30,041
[SPEAKER_22]: I have to say...

1111
01:18:30,061 --> 01:18:30,683
[SPEAKER_22]: Hold on, hold on.

1112
01:18:30,803 --> 01:18:31,224
[SPEAKER_22]: Is this news to you?

1113
01:18:31,244 --> 01:18:35,753
[SPEAKER_22]: That is news to me, that doctors are insisting that you have to come within the 48 hours.

1114
01:18:35,733 --> 01:18:40,201
[SPEAKER_07]: A doctor's appointment is to turn up outside the appointment at 8 o'clock in the morning waiting for you.

1115
01:18:40,221 --> 01:18:47,916
[SPEAKER_22]: The whole purpose of this was that people used to be able, used not to be able rather, to get an appointment with the GP within the 48 hours.

1116
01:18:47,936 --> 01:18:50,120
[SPEAKER_22]: Now obviously it shouldn't work in that way because that would be absurd.

1117
01:18:50,140 --> 01:18:52,183
[SPEAKER_07]: No, you can't get it at all unless it is within the 48 hours.

1118
01:18:52,364 --> 01:18:54,147
[SPEAKER_22]: Anybody else have this experience?

1119
01:18:55,814 --> 01:18:57,316
[SPEAKER_30]: What?

1120
01:18:57,476 --> 01:19:00,099
[SPEAKER_38]: Just explain it to the Prime Minister.

1121
01:19:00,300 --> 01:19:06,828
[SPEAKER_38]: If I ring up and ask, say, on the Monday for an appointment, on the Wednesday, no, you'll have to ring back Wednesday morning.

1122
01:19:08,290 --> 01:19:10,973
[SPEAKER_22]: Sorry, but there's quite a lot of people who have said this.

1123
01:19:10,993 --> 01:19:15,679
[SPEAKER_22]: I understand that, but surely they're not saying to you that you have to have it quicker than you wanted.

1124
01:19:16,385 --> 01:19:23,086
[SPEAKER_30]: They're saying you can't make the appointment until you're within the time frame that allows it to be 48 hours.

1125
01:19:23,347 --> 01:19:25,815
[SPEAKER_30]: So you can't make it today, you come back and make it on Wednesday.

1126
01:19:25,975 --> 01:19:29,145
[SPEAKER_07]: Even if the doctor asked you to come back a week later?

1127
01:19:29,176 --> 01:19:32,262
[SPEAKER_22]: I will look into that.

1128
01:19:32,483 --> 01:19:39,998
[SPEAKER_22]: The purpose of the target, just so you know, is that it used to be the case that people would phone the GP and not be able to get an appointment for a week or two weeks when they wanted it quickly.

1129
01:19:40,419 --> 01:19:42,803
[SPEAKER_22]: I agree, the target obviously should not work in that way.

1130
01:19:43,284 --> 01:19:44,667
[SPEAKER_22]: That is a perfectly sensible point.

1131
01:19:44,707 --> 01:19:45,348
[SPEAKER_22]: I will have a look at it.

1132
01:19:46,831 --> 01:19:48,334
[SPEAKER_22]: It obviously should not work like that.

1133
01:19:48,354 --> 01:19:50,138
[SPEAKER_22]: The purpose of these targets

1134
01:19:50,118 --> 01:19:58,771
[SPEAKER_22]: just so that I explain the situation, is to try and make sure that you get minimum quality and standards and are seen quickly.

1135
01:19:59,031 --> 01:20:01,374
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, obviously, it should not work in the opposite way.

1136
01:20:02,276 --> 01:20:05,660
[SPEAKER_30]: OK. Just before we started on tax, just one question on tax.

1137
01:20:06,121 --> 01:20:16,817
[SPEAKER_30]: At the last election, you were asked on Newsnight whether you thought any reasonable person shouldn't suppose, because there was no commitment not to increase national insurance, that the tax would go up.

1138
01:20:17,257 --> 01:20:19,180
[SPEAKER_30]: And you said they shouldn't.

1139
01:20:19,632 --> 01:20:20,153
[SPEAKER_30]: suppose.

1140
01:20:21,154 --> 01:20:22,916
[SPEAKER_30]: Should or shouldn't we suppose now?

1141
01:20:22,956 --> 01:20:26,200
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, the plans that we have got are fully costed and taken account of.

1142
01:20:26,261 --> 01:20:27,402
[SPEAKER_22]: They were last time round.

1143
01:20:27,502 --> 01:20:27,883
[SPEAKER_22]: They were.

1144
01:20:28,584 --> 01:20:36,053
[SPEAKER_22]: What happened was, as I just explained, we got the report on healthcare spending that said if you want to reach the European average, you are going to have to put more money in.

1145
01:20:36,093 --> 01:20:38,937
[SPEAKER_22]: Should we or shouldn't we now suppose there will be a further increase?

1146
01:20:39,157 --> 01:20:40,359
[SPEAKER_22]: I can't sit and write the budget.

1147
01:20:40,379 --> 01:20:49,150
[SPEAKER_30]: You are the Prime Minister and your friend is the Chancellor of the Exchequer.

1148
01:20:49,872 --> 01:20:56,983
[SPEAKER_30]: And we've seen him side by side throughout this election campaign, so presumably you know what's in his mind.

1149
01:20:57,684 --> 01:21:00,448
[SPEAKER_22]: Yes, of course I know what's in his mind.

1150
01:21:00,468 --> 01:21:05,615
[SPEAKER_22]: And what's in his mind is to carry on running the strongest economy in the Western world, and thank goodness he's been doing it.

1151
01:21:05,796 --> 01:21:06,957
[SPEAKER_22]: Or to become Prime Minister.

1152
01:21:07,078 --> 01:21:08,279
[SPEAKER_22]: Well, that may be there too.

1153
01:21:08,900 --> 01:21:14,729
[SPEAKER_22]: But before we get to that stage, David, we've got to win this election, and there's a long way to go.

1154
01:21:15,610 --> 01:21:15,810
[SPEAKER_30]: Oh, right.

1155
01:21:15,831 --> 01:21:17,533
[SPEAKER_30]: Oh, so he is going to become Prime Minister?

1156
01:21:17,513 --> 01:21:19,238
[SPEAKER_22]: No, I haven't said that either.

1157
01:21:19,379 --> 01:21:27,182
[SPEAKER_22]: I've simply said that before anybody has the right to say they're going to be Prime Minister, we've got to get through the next week.

1158
01:21:27,202 --> 01:21:30,713
[SPEAKER_30]: You've said you're going to stand down during this next Parliament.

1159
01:21:30,980 --> 01:21:32,903
[SPEAKER_30]: Are you going to vote for him as leader of the Labour Party?

1160
01:21:33,284 --> 01:21:36,750
[SPEAKER_22]: I think before we get to that, we better win this election first.

1161
01:21:37,170 --> 01:21:38,252
[SPEAKER_30]: No, whether we win...

1162
01:21:38,272 --> 01:21:51,013
[SPEAKER_22]: I've answered this question 1,000 times and I've always said that Gordon would make an excellent Prime Minister but I'm not getting into selecting the next Prime Minister when I can't even be sure I'm going to be in my own... No, but we're just talking about the leader of the Labour Party.

1163
01:21:50,993 --> 01:21:52,996
[SPEAKER_22]: and whether you win the election or not.

1164
01:21:53,036 --> 01:21:58,645
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm just asking you, when the leadership battle comes, you've announced it's going to come because you said you're standing down.

1165
01:21:58,866 --> 01:22:00,248
[SPEAKER_30]: When it comes, will you vote for Gordon Brown?

1166
01:22:00,268 --> 01:22:02,652
[SPEAKER_22]: At some point, you have to stand down in any event, which is why I answered the question.

1167
01:22:02,672 --> 01:22:03,833
[SPEAKER_22]: Will you vote for your good friend Gordon Brown?

1168
01:22:03,854 --> 01:22:05,817
[SPEAKER_22]: And let us wait and see what happens at a later stage.

1169
01:22:05,957 --> 01:22:09,402
[SPEAKER_22]: I've always said, however, he would make an extremely good Prime Minister of this country.

1170
01:22:09,422 --> 01:22:10,584
[SPEAKER_22]: But you haven't decided yet.

1171
01:22:10,644 --> 01:22:12,968
[SPEAKER_22]: It's not that I haven't decided, it's that I'm not getting in.

1172
01:22:12,948 --> 01:22:19,336
[SPEAKER_22]: I'm not getting into those questions until we've decided this election and actually that's for the public to decide.

1173
01:22:19,356 --> 01:22:20,898
[SPEAKER_30]: Well I wonder what he has to do to get your vote.

1174
01:22:20,938 --> 01:22:22,080
[SPEAKER_30]: Anyway let's go on to another question.

1175
01:22:22,460 --> 01:22:23,882
[SPEAKER_30]: Andrew Thwaites please.

1176
01:22:24,303 --> 01:22:24,904
[SPEAKER_30]: Andrew Thwaites.

1177
01:22:25,184 --> 01:22:35,918
[SPEAKER_29]: Yes, I wonder if you could clarify what you meant in your 2001 manifesto when you said we will not introduce top-up fees and have legislated to prevent them.

1178
01:22:45,668 --> 01:22:49,113
[SPEAKER_22]: What we've done now is introduce a completely different system of student finance.

1179
01:22:52,298 --> 01:22:57,566
[SPEAKER_22]: It's not top-up fees as with the old system where you paid the fees as you went through university.

1180
01:22:57,807 --> 01:23:00,050
[SPEAKER_22]: It's important people understand what this proposal is.

1181
01:23:00,932 --> 01:23:05,078
[SPEAKER_22]: From now on, people will pay no fees as they go through university.

1182
01:23:05,058 --> 01:23:11,673
[SPEAKER_22]: They will then, and there will be maintenance grants, reintroduce £3,000 a year for the poorest students.

1183
01:23:12,194 --> 01:23:19,590
[SPEAKER_22]: Then when students graduate, they will pay back into the pot a fair repayment system based on their ability to pay.

1184
01:23:19,670 --> 01:23:20,552
[SPEAKER_22]: So, for example,

1185
01:23:20,532 --> 01:23:29,281
[SPEAKER_22]: If you stop work, or you're a woman and you start to raise a family, or, for example, for any reason, you become ill or unemployed, you don't pay.

1186
01:23:29,802 --> 01:23:40,133
[SPEAKER_22]: And the system is one in which we're able to get more money into the universities, more people able to go to university, without anyone having to pay fees as they go through the system.

1187
01:23:40,233 --> 01:23:41,655
[SPEAKER_22]: You didn't say that in the manifesto, did you?

1188
01:23:41,675 --> 01:23:44,498
[SPEAKER_22]: No, I didn't say that about maintenance grants being reintroduced for poor students.

1189
01:23:44,518 --> 01:23:47,321
[SPEAKER_30]: You just said you weren't going to introduce top-up fees and had legislated to prevent them.

1190
01:23:47,341 --> 01:23:49,543
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes, but where's the legislation to prevent them, Tony?

1191
01:23:49,523 --> 01:23:50,424
[SPEAKER_29]: Where is it?

1192
01:23:50,625 --> 01:23:52,968
[SPEAKER_29]: Yes, but this is... No, I want... Where is it?

1193
01:23:53,469 --> 01:23:55,972
[SPEAKER_29]: Where is the legislation to prevent top-up fees?

1194
01:23:56,213 --> 01:23:58,356
[SPEAKER_29]: You said there was legislation to prevent them.

1195
01:23:58,716 --> 01:23:59,357
[SPEAKER_22]: Where is it?

1196
01:23:59,618 --> 01:24:00,859
[SPEAKER_22]: We had legislated...

1197
01:24:00,879 --> 01:24:01,300
[SPEAKER_22]: It doesn't exist.

1198
01:24:01,340 --> 01:24:01,981
[SPEAKER_22]: No, I'm sorry.

1199
01:24:02,341 --> 01:24:06,908
[SPEAKER_22]: It existed because we said we were going not to introduce...

1200
01:24:06,888 --> 01:24:08,530
[SPEAKER_22]: When did it exist?

1201
01:24:08,930 --> 01:24:12,955
[SPEAKER_22]: The legislation prevented us introducing top-up fees.

1202
01:24:13,396 --> 01:24:18,001
[SPEAKER_22]: The legislation we then introduced in this Parliament changes the system entirely.

1203
01:24:18,462 --> 01:24:24,509
[SPEAKER_22]: And instead of paying any fees as you go through university, you make a fair repayment after you graduate.

1204
01:24:24,549 --> 01:24:32,659
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, the only alternative to that, with the greatest respect, is either the Lib Dem one, which is to impose this 50% top rate of tax and pay for everything through that,

1205
01:24:32,639 --> 01:24:41,134
[SPEAKER_22]: or the Conservative one, which is to privatise the student loan book, which will end up with graduates paying a real credit card rate of interest on their student debt.

1206
01:24:41,414 --> 01:24:43,899
[SPEAKER_22]: Now, I happen to think our system is fairer.

1207
01:24:43,919 --> 01:24:47,505
[SPEAKER_22]: We already, incidentally, in this country... You shake your head, but it's true.

1208
01:24:47,685 --> 01:24:48,707
[SPEAKER_29]: I think it's easy for you

1209
01:24:48,687 --> 01:24:50,569
[SPEAKER_29]: you to say you went to university for free.

1210
01:24:50,910 --> 01:24:53,533
[SPEAKER_29]: You went to university for free and there was an option.

1211
01:24:53,773 --> 01:24:55,456
[SPEAKER_29]: You gave us one option as students.

1212
01:24:55,476 --> 01:24:56,557
[SPEAKER_29]: You gave us one option.

1213
01:24:56,817 --> 01:24:57,919
[SPEAKER_29]: It's this way or nothing.

1214
01:24:57,939 --> 01:25:00,001
[SPEAKER_29]: And now you're saying, oh, but it's fairer.

1215
01:25:00,021 --> 01:25:03,926
[SPEAKER_29]: What would be fairer was if you, people that have graduated, started paying back too.

1216
01:25:04,287 --> 01:25:08,492
[SPEAKER_29]: And I know there's a lot of people.

1217
01:25:08,512 --> 01:25:10,054
[SPEAKER_29]: There are loads of people that have graduated that would not mind doing that.

1218
01:25:10,034 --> 01:25:16,609
[SPEAKER_29]: And it's easy for you to sit there and say to me, who's now got debts of £8,000 and £10,000, that it's fairer.

1219
01:25:16,649 --> 01:25:19,757
[SPEAKER_29]: It's not fairer on me, because you got your education for free, Mr Prime Minister.

1220
01:25:19,797 --> 01:25:24,768
[SPEAKER_22]: Yeah, but, Andrew, when I was going through university, there were 5% of school leavers that went through university.

1221
01:25:25,450 --> 01:25:25,650
[SPEAKER_22]: Right?

1222
01:25:25,750 --> 01:25:28,617
[SPEAKER_22]: Now it is 40% of school leavers.

1223
01:25:28,597 --> 01:25:31,361
[SPEAKER_22]: I put more investment, or you do, actually, as the taxpayer.

1224
01:25:31,381 --> 01:25:39,651
[SPEAKER_22]: You put more investment into a student's education at university than you do into a secondary school pupil's or a primary school pupil's.

1225
01:25:40,052 --> 01:25:44,738
[SPEAKER_22]: Even under our new system, five-sixths of the money comes from the ordinary taxpayer.

1226
01:25:44,758 --> 01:25:52,968
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't think it's too much, instead of taking more money from the ordinary taxpayer, to ask people, when they graduate, to pay something back into the pot.

1227
01:25:53,208 --> 01:25:57,574
[SPEAKER_22]: I think that's a darn sight fairer than putting taxes on the ordinary population.

1228
01:26:00,035 --> 01:26:09,868
[SPEAKER_35]: Mr Blair, I made an important observation since September, in that every MP I've spoken to, and when I ask them about you, they all say that you're a great politician.

1229
01:26:10,129 --> 01:26:14,314
[SPEAKER_35]: But isn't it worrying that none of them, and I mean none of them, have actually referred to you as a good leader?

1230
01:26:16,357 --> 01:26:19,842
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't quite know who you've spoken to, obviously, but it's...

1231
01:26:21,484 --> 01:26:22,025
[SPEAKER_22]: The decision...

1232
01:26:22,045 --> 01:26:23,246
[SPEAKER_30]: I tried to ask him to give the names.

1233
01:26:23,567 --> 01:26:26,831
[SPEAKER_30]: No, I don't, but... You can give the names.

1234
01:26:27,071 --> 01:26:28,333
[SPEAKER_30]: Go on, then, name the names.

1235
01:26:28,694 --> 01:26:29,755
[SPEAKER_30]: Name them.

1236
01:26:30,275 --> 01:26:31,323
[SPEAKER_30]: Serious?

1237
01:26:31,343 --> 01:26:31,426
[SPEAKER_30]: Yes.

1238
01:26:34,122 --> 01:26:35,784
[SPEAKER_22]: We're always serious on this show.

1239
01:26:36,165 --> 01:26:38,168
[SPEAKER_22]: Look, you're going to have to make up your own mind about that.

1240
01:26:38,749 --> 01:26:42,073
[SPEAKER_22]: Look, there's no point in me sitting here and saying, oh, yes, I am a good leader or I'm not.

1241
01:26:42,093 --> 01:26:43,996
[SPEAKER_22]: You're going to have to decide who you want to lead this country.

1242
01:26:44,237 --> 01:26:48,122
[SPEAKER_22]: And on May the 6th, you're either going to have Michael Howard walk into number 10 Downing Street or me.

1243
01:26:48,643 --> 01:26:58,637
[SPEAKER_22]: And if you want to keep the economy strong and the investment in our public services there and the measures to help families in this country that we've introduced in the past few years, you should vote for the leadership that's delivered.

1244
01:26:58,657 --> 01:26:59,418
[SPEAKER_22]: Hang on a second.

1245
01:26:59,539 --> 01:27:00,360
[SPEAKER_30]: Hang on a second.

1246
01:27:00,380 --> 01:27:01,902
[SPEAKER_30]: The woman in cream there.

1247
01:27:01,882 --> 01:27:03,828
[SPEAKER_43]: I was going back to the university question.

1248
01:27:04,069 --> 01:27:04,149
[SPEAKER_43]: Yes.

1249
01:27:04,169 --> 01:27:11,230
[SPEAKER_43]: Do you think that perhaps 40% of school leavers going to university is too many because a lot of them can't get jobs once they leave university?

1250
01:27:11,892 --> 01:27:12,634
[SPEAKER_22]: I'll be brief, Mr Blair, if you want.

1251
01:27:13,576 --> 01:27:15,839
[SPEAKER_22]: It's entirely up to them.

1252
01:27:15,999 --> 01:27:17,621
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't force anyone to go to university.

1253
01:27:18,022 --> 01:27:22,788
[SPEAKER_22]: But if people want to go, you've got to have a system of funding universities that's fair.

1254
01:27:23,229 --> 01:27:25,632
[SPEAKER_22]: Fair to the student, fair to the taxpayer.

1255
01:27:25,652 --> 01:27:38,509
[SPEAKER_22]: A system that is linked to people's ability to pay when they pay nothing going through university is a lot fairer than a system where we prevent, as the Conservatives would do, by a cap on the university numbers, people who want to go to university going there.

1256
01:27:38,749 --> 01:27:41,473
[SPEAKER_22]: I think that's a return to the elitism of the past and I don't want it in this country.

1257
01:27:41,453 --> 01:27:43,441
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr Blair, can I just ask you one last question?

1258
01:27:43,461 --> 01:27:50,147
[SPEAKER_30]: We've had Mr Kennedy in that chair, we've had Mr Howard in that chair, why wouldn't you debate directly, face to face, with them?

1259
01:28:07,323 --> 01:28:09,785
[SPEAKER_22]: I debate every week in the House of Commons with Michael Howard.

1260
01:28:10,125 --> 01:28:11,527
[SPEAKER_22]: I'm here to answer questions tonight.

1261
01:28:12,267 --> 01:28:23,577
[SPEAKER_22]: And I probably do more discussions, not just with audiences like this, but with people when we talk about the issues than any politician before me.

1262
01:28:24,017 --> 01:28:24,798
[SPEAKER_30]: All right.

1263
01:28:24,818 --> 01:28:26,520
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr. Blair, Mr. Blair, thank you.

1264
01:28:26,960 --> 01:28:28,281
[SPEAKER_30]: Thank you very much.

1265
01:28:28,802 --> 01:28:29,342
[SPEAKER_30]: Sorry, hang on.

1266
01:28:29,382 --> 01:28:29,923
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you very much.

1267
01:28:29,943 --> 01:28:30,583
[SPEAKER_30]: No, no, no, no, no.

1268
01:28:30,603 --> 01:28:31,984
[SPEAKER_30]: We've reached the end of our time.

1269
01:28:32,145 --> 01:28:32,725
[SPEAKER_30]: I'm sorry.

1270
01:28:32,945 --> 01:28:33,586
[SPEAKER_30]: Will you be quiet?

1271
01:28:34,026 --> 01:28:36,148
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr. Blair, thank you very much indeed.

1272
01:28:39,385 --> 01:28:44,333
[SPEAKER_30]: And... That... That...

1273
01:28:44,353 --> 01:28:45,455
[SPEAKER_30]: Sit down, if you would.

1274
01:28:45,475 --> 01:28:49,081
[SPEAKER_30]: That ends this special edition of Question Time.

1275
01:28:49,101 --> 01:28:53,950
[SPEAKER_30]: I'd just like to thank the party leaders who took part and thank all of you who came here today.

1276
01:28:53,970 --> 01:28:54,811
[SPEAKER_30]: But will you be quiet?

1277
01:28:54,831 --> 01:28:56,294
[SPEAKER_30]: You can speak to Mr Blair in a moment.

1278
01:28:56,754 --> 01:29:01,242
[SPEAKER_30]: But just be quiet while we end the... Will you be quiet while we finish the programme, please?

1279
01:29:01,694 --> 01:29:14,165
[SPEAKER_30]: All right, let me just say lastly, for viewers in Wales and Scotland, there are details on our website of important editions of Question Time tomorrow on BBC One, which have the leaders of Plaid Cymru and the Scottish National Party on them.

1280
01:29:14,586 --> 01:29:20,171
[SPEAKER_30]: Next Thursday, Question Time is off the air, of course, because of the election, but we'll be back the following Thursday.

1281
01:29:20,191 --> 01:29:21,552
[SPEAKER_30]: We're in Leeds on May the 12th.

1282
01:29:21,572 --> 01:29:22,973
[SPEAKER_30]: We're in Edinburgh on May the 19th.

1283
01:29:23,013 --> 01:29:24,434
[SPEAKER_30]: You know the number to ring if you'd like to come.

1284
01:29:24,454 --> 01:29:25,415
[SPEAKER_30]: It'd be very nice if you could.

1285
01:29:26,336 --> 01:29:28,558
[SPEAKER_30]: And, of course, you can comment on our website, as always.

1286
01:29:28,598 --> 01:29:31,701
[SPEAKER_30]: In the meantime, from all of us here in London tonight, good night.

